<DIV1 TYPE="masque">
<PB REF="12">
<HEAD>MEROPE.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>An Apartment in the Palace.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>MEROPE, <HI>mournful, on a Couch</HI>.</STAGE>
<STAGE>ISMENE, <HI>leaning melancholy, below</HI>.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Soft Mu&s;ick.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter, to</HI> ISMENE, <HI>a Singer</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISMENE.</SPEAKER>
<L>SEE! where the lone maje&s;tic Mourner weeps;</L>
<L>Lo&s;t, even $o <HI>Mu&s;ick's</HI> Power! &mdash;try: &s;train each Note,</L>
<L>In Melody's wide Compa&s;s.&mdash;Happily,</L>
<L>Some Change, through <HI>&s;ad</HI>, to <HI>lively</HI>, may have Force,</L>
<L>To &s;trike recov'ring Sen&s;e, and wake Regard.</L>
<L>&mdash;Fir&s;t, in low Sympathy of <HI>Sorrow's Softne&s;s</HI>,</L>
<L>Sooth her dejected Soul&mdash;then, &s;tart at once</L>
<L>To <HI>Swells</HI> of <HI>Joy</HI>&mdash;and &s;torm Attention's Ear.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="14" REF="13"><HI>Song: by the &s;ame Voice, interchangeably, to Flute and Trumpet: which are heard as at &s;ome Di&s;|tance without.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Flute.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Stay, &s;tay, <HI>De&s;pair!</HI>&mdash;begone vain <HI>Hoper! go</HI>,</L>
<L>Sorrow can hear no Voice, but That of <HI>Woe</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Trumpet.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Away with your <HI>Tears</HI> where Enjoyment &s;hou'd flow,</L>
<L>Bid Defiance to <HI>Pain</HI> &mdash;let her go: let her go.</L>
<L>Do the Gods love <HI>Complainers?</HI> &mdash;No. No. No.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Flute.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Ah!&mdash;tis in <HI>vain</HI> to &s;trive&mdash;farewel <HI>believing</HI>.</L>
<L><HI>Death</HI> is the &s;ure &s;hort <HI>Road</HI>&mdash;to &s;hun <HI>deceiving</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Trumpet.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Laugh</HI> at your Woes: and make 'em <HI>plea&s;ing</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Flute.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>No, no&mdash;the Pains we chu&s;e de&s;pi&s;e all <HI>Ea&s;ing</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Trumpet.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Hope for a <HI>Cure</HI> where Nature plac'd it.</L>
<L>Life is &s;o &s;hort, 'tis a Shame to wa&s;te it.</L>
<L><HI>Seek</HI> for Delight: and <HI>de&s;erve</HI> to ta&s;te it.</L>
<L><HI>Age</HI> will come on, and allow no Lea&s;ure.</L>
<L><HI>Youth</HI> will be gone, and away goes Plea&s;ure.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Flute.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Re&s;t and the Grave will meet.&mdash;but ah!&mdash;<HI>till then</HI>,</L>
<L>Joy <HI>flies</HI> the vain Pur&s;uit of <HI>hopele&s;s Men</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE>Merop&eacute; <HI>ri&s;es, and comes forward</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Go&mdash;the Queen ri&s;es.&mdash;Angels, that have tun'd,</L>
<L><HI>Reward</HI> the vocal Magic of thy Song.
<STAGE><HI>Exit Singer.</HI></STAGE></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Let me, when, <HI>next</HI>, thy too officious Love,</L>
<L>Faithful <HI>I&s;men&eacute;</HI>, trys th' harmonious Charm,</L>
<L>Let me, have Mu&s;ick, <HI>&s;olemn</HI>, all, and <HI>&s;low</HI>,</L>
<L>Sad-&s;uited to my Thoughts&mdash;Why &s;hou'd I hear,</L>
<L>Who have no Power to <HI>ta&s;te</HI>, &s;uch <HI>&s;pritely</HI> Notes,</L>
<L>As they who are more Happy, find more Sweet?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Why, when the <HI>Gods</HI> grow gentle, are <HI>You</HI> &s;ad?</L>
<L>You felt their <HI>Anger</HI>, &s;harply.&mdash;Now they &s;mile,</L>
<L><HI>Embrace</HI> their proffer'd Bounty&mdash;All the Lords</L>
<L>Of glad <HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI>, in full Senate met,</L>
<L>Take Mea&s;ures to proclaim you <HI>reigning</HI> Queen:</L>
<L>You, whom di&s;tre&s;s but brightens!&mdash;to who&s;e Charms,</L>
<L><PB N="15" REF="14">Made aweful by your Grief, Woes add new Maje&s;ty!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What, no News yet, of <HI>Narbas?</HI> or my <HI>Son?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>May it be &s;oon!&mdash;No Prince, of Birth like His,</L>
<L>Where-e're conceal'd, can '&s;cape &s;uch Search, unknown.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Will ye, at length, ye Powers, reward my Tears?</L>
<L><HI>Will</HI> ye, at la&s;t, re&s;tore <HI>Eumenes</HI>, to me?</L>
<L>&mdash;If he yet lives&mdash;this only remnant Heir</L>
<L>Of his wrong'd Mother's Mi&s;eries!&mdash;oh, <HI>&s;ave</HI> him.</L>
<L>From his dear Brea&s;t, &s;trike wide the Murd'rer's Dagger.</L>
<L>Is he not <HI>Your's?</HI> a Branch, from Great <HI>Alcides?</HI></L>
<L>What, tho'&mdash;(forget it, and be <HI>hu&s;h'd</HI>, O Faith!)</L>
<L>What, tho' to Traitors pro&s;p'rous Swords, you gave</L>
<L>His <HI>Father</HI>'s fated Life&mdash;ah, yet! de&s;ert not</L>
<L>This Image of his Form, that fills my Soul.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Dear, tho' he doubtle&s;s was, and ju&s;tly mourn'd,</L>
<L>Shou'd you <HI>exclude</HI> all &s;en&s;e of Bli&s;s, be&s;ide?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I am a <HI>Mother:</HI>&mdash;with a Mother's <HI>Fears</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>But, can a Mother's Fears efface the Stamp</L>
<L>Of <HI>Hero</HI>'s Soul, that marks a Race like yours?</L>
<L>&mdash;Sweet, tho' his infant Smiles, they dwell, too fix'd,</L>
<L>Too deep, on your touch'd Memory!&mdash; Long Years</L>
<L>Are pa&s;t, &s;ince fir&s;t you lo&s;t him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Lo&s;t</HI> him?&mdash;<HI>never</HI>.&mdash;</L>
<L>In twice &s;even dreadful years, no Moment's Light</L>
<L>Broke on my Eyes, but brought <HI>His Image</HI> with it.</L>
<L>Why tell'&s;t thou me of <HI>Time?</HI>&mdash;Days, Months, and Years,</L>
<L>Have grown; but with 'em grew, my Pain, to lo&s;e him.</L>
<L>&mdash;Weigh that la&s;t fatal Hint, thy Father &s;ent me.</L>
<L><HI>Hope</HI>, &s;aid th' Alarmer &s;oon, <HI>to &s;ee Eum&egrave;nes</HI></L>
<L>All, you wou'd wi&s;h:&mdash;<HI>fear</HI> All, from <HI>Poliphontes</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Wi&s;ely, you fear him.&mdash;but 'twere wi&s;er, &s;till,</L>
<L>So fearing, to <HI>prevent</HI> him.&mdash;Hear the <HI>States:</HI></L>
<L>Quit, at their Prayer, this <HI>Regent</HI>'s Name&mdash;be <HI>crown'd:</HI></L>
<L>And ri&s;e, <HI>indeed</HI> the <HI>Queen</HI> they meant to make you.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Is not the Crown my <HI>Son's?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>A Son, &s;o lov'd&mdash;</L>
<L>Shou'd he return, wou'd thank&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Peri&s;h the Heart,</L>
<L>That, meanly proud, and poorly fill'd for <HI>Self</HI>,</L>
<L>Swells, from Another's <HI>Lo&s;&s;es!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="16" REF="15">
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Public Intere&s;t&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Cur&s;e on <HI>all</HI> Int're&s;t, that includes not <HI>Hone&s;ty!</HI></L>
<L>&mdash;But, here, even Int're&s;t brings no Plea to tempt me,</L>
<L>What can a <HI>childle&s;s</HI> Mother hope, from Empire?</L>
<L>What has Di&s;tre&s;s to do, with Pomp's vain Splendor?</L>
<L>&mdash;I &s;ee the very Light of Heaven, with <HI>Pain</HI>.</L>
<L>Ne'er &s;hall brief Comfort chear the&s;e bla&s;ted Eyes,</L>
<L>That &s;aw my bleeding Lord, my murder'd Children;</L>
<L>Saw my Friends fall: Saw <HI>Men</HI> and <HI>Gods</HI> for&s;ake me.</L>
<L>&mdash;O, Guilt! O, Perfidy!&mdash;oh! Death's dire Day!</L>
<L>Pre&s;ent, forever, to my frighted Soul.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oft have I wept,&mdash;to hear that Day's &s;ad Tale.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I hear it <HI>now!</HI> &mdash;Even yet their Cries ri&s;e round me!</L>
<L>Save, &s;ave, the <HI>King</HI>&mdash;&s;ave the poor ga&s;ping <HI>Princes:</HI></L>
<L>Save the di&s;tracted <HI>Queen!</HI>&mdash;I &s;cream&mdash;I fly&mdash;</L>
<L>On every Side I turn meet battling Crowds:</L>
<L>Swords, glitt'ring Spears, loud Shouts, and mingled Groanings.</L>
<L>Meet, <HI>la&s;t</HI>&mdash;a Sight&mdash;beyond all Sen&s;e of Horror!</L>
<L>Meet&mdash;an expiring Hu&s;band's out &s;tretch'd Eye,</L>
<L>Strain'd, with a death-mix'd Tenderne&s;s on mine&mdash;</L>
<L>And &s;truggling from his Blood, to reach, and cla&s;p me.</L>
<L>&mdash;There, two departing infant Suff'rers <HI>fell</HI>,</L>
<L>The Elde&s;t, of our Loves!&mdash;duteous, in <HI>Death!</HI></L>
<L>Cro&s;s the King's Brea&s;t, they threw their little Bodies,</L>
<L>And lent <HI>their</HI> Hand's weak Aid&mdash;to &s;ave their Father.</L>
<L>&mdash;<HI>Only Eumenes</HI> &mdash;'&s;cap'd th' A&s;&s;a&s;&s;in's Fury.</L>
<L>Some interpo&s;ing <HI>God</HI> vouch&s;af'd to <HI>veil</HI> him:</L>
<L>And He, who &s;creen'd him, then, may, <HI>once</HI>, re&s;tore him.</L>
<L>&mdash;<HI>Narbas</HI>, thy wi&s;e, thy faithful Father, bore him</L>
<L>Far from my Sight&mdash;to &s;ome dark &s;afe Retreat</L>
<L>Some <HI>De&s;art</HI>,&mdash; barren of Di&s;tre&s;s, and Man!</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>MEROPE, ISMENE, EURICLES.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Madam!&mdash; Lord <HI>Euricles</HI>&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Welcome &mdash;what Hope?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Wou'd, I cou'd an&s;wer&mdash;what you wi&s;h to hear!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="17" REF="16">
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Not what I wi&s;h&mdash;but what Heaven wills, reply.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Vain was our Search&mdash;From <HI>Peneus'</HI> Bank, it &s;pread,</L>
<L>O'er va&s;t <HI>Olympus:</HI> far and wide, through <HI>Greece</HI>,</L>
<L>Enquiry, lab'ring, lo&s;t its fruitle&s;s Prayer.</L>
<L>De&s;cription cou'd not wake the lea&s;t Idea.</L>
<L>None knew, none ever heard of, <HI>Narbas'</HI> Name!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Alas! he breaths no more&mdash;my Son is <HI>dead</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>So, Fear makes real every fan&s;ied Woe.</L>
<L>&mdash;You've heard, that, on Report of this new Peace,</L>
<L>My Father guides him, &s;ecret, to your Wi&s;h.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Thence grew his Fear! Good <HI>Narbas</HI>, wi&s;ely loyal,</L>
<L>Veils his Return, and cautiou&s;ly conveys him.</L>
<L><HI>Narbas</HI> knows All his Dangers&mdash;I, mean while,</L>
<L>Watch, with a guardful Eye the&s;e Murd'rers Motions:</L>
<L>And, with determin'd Hand, prepare to &s;ave him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>On Faith &s;o try'd as Thine, even Woe leans ea&s;y,</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Doubt but my <HI>Power</HI>'s Defect: My <HI>Will</HI> finds none.</L>
<L>&mdash;But I have News more threat'ning.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Can</HI> That be?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Th' a&s;&s;embled Senate vote, in warm Debate,</L>
<L>A Partner in your Crown. &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Pre&s;umptuous Care!</L>
<L>You &s;hou'd have call'd it <HI>In&s;ult</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Words were vain.</L>
<L>Truth, un&s;u&s;tain'd by Power, but fights, to <HI>fall</HI>.</L>
<L>The partial <HI>People</HI> roar for <HI>Poliphontes:</HI></L>
<L>And Right, and Law, and Pity, &s;ink before him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Can Fortune, then, reduce the Great to <HI>Pity!</HI></L>
<L>Can Kings, in their own Realms, contract to <HI>Slaves</HI>,</L>
<L>He, who counts <HI>Jove</HI>, among his crown'd Progenitors,</L>
<L>Come He, to Subjects, to explore a <HI>Ma&s;ter!</HI></L>
<L>&mdash;Shame on thy <HI>Lies</HI>, O Loyalty!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Your Friends&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I have <HI>no</HI> Friends&mdash;Yes&mdash;Thee; good <HI>Eur$cles!</HI></L>
<L>Forgive me, that I wrong'd thee&mdash;'twas my <HI>Sorrow</HI>.</L>
<L>The <HI>Wretched</HI>, in their Pain, forget the <HI>Kind</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;Blocks! Stones!&mdash;Rebellion hardens Men, to Brutes!</L>
<L><PB N="18" REF="17">Sen&s;ele&s;s, alike, to Gratitude, and Glory,</L>
<L>Even <HI>Names</HI>, as well as Natures, change their Meaning.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Dear, to their Hearts, they hold their Sov'reign's Name;</L>
<L>And weep his honour'd Mem'ry.&mdash;For <HI>Your&s;elf</HI>,</L>
<L>Their Love outgoes De&s;cription.&mdash;They but fear.</L>
<L>Your Sex's widow'd Weakne&s;s <HI>in&s;ecure</HI>;</L>
<L>And <HI>Poliphontes' Sword</HI>, they think, will guard it.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Ever in&s;ulted, now by Friends, now Forms.</L>
<L>Princes are <HI>Slaves</HI>, that Subjects may have <HI>Liberty</HI>.</L>
<L>Driven, or attracted, ever!&mdash;why was a King</L>
<L>Call'd <HI>Ruler?</HI> infamous Abu&s;e of Phra&s;e!</L>
<L>Faction and Clamour are, <HI>more</HI>, Kings than He.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Something mu&s;t be re&s;olv'd, to check their &s;peed.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Yes&mdash;let me <HI>face</HI> the&s;e Lords, of Kings, and Law:</L>
<L><HI>Comets</HI> of Empire! the&s;e portent'ous Stars,</L>
<L>That &s;parkle by the Fire they <HI>&s;teal</HI> from Maje&s;ty;</L>
<L>I will go dart Truth's Light'ning in their Eyes,</L>
<L>And thunder in their Ears the Rights of Thrones.</L>
<L>I will revive lo&s;t Sen&s;e of Tru&s;t, and Duty:</L>
<L>I will a&s;&s;ert their Sov'reign's near Return.
<STAGE><HI>going.</HI></STAGE></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh, Heav'n! be wary&mdash;That Way, Ruin lies.</L>
<L>Their Tyrant Leader &s;tarts, already fir'd,</L>
<L>By that Alarm: and dreams, of what he dreads.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What <HI>can</HI> he, more&mdash;&s;o much already done?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Jealous of Danger, Men make Ha&s;te in Guilt:</L>
<L>Work, to be &s;afe, and hold no Means too wicked.</L>
<L><HI>Mycen$</HI>, but by Faction, freed from Faction,</L>
<L>Weigh'd like a Conque&s;t, he computes His <HI>own</HI>.</L>
<L>No Tye &s;o &s;acred binds endanger'd Valour,</L>
<L>Where hot Ambition &s;purs it&mdash;Every Rampart</L>
<L>Gives Way, before him. <HI>Law</HI>, corrupted, guards him.</L>
<L><HI>Wealth</HI> dre&s;&s;es, <HI>Poverty</HI> attends, <HI>Pride</HI> leads:</L>
<L>And <HI>Prie&s;thood</HI> pre&s;&s;es Gods who <HI>hate</HI>&mdash;to <HI>&s;erve</HI> him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I &s;ee th' Aby&s;s, before me&mdash;Let it be.</L>
<L>If I plunge in, and cru&s;h this <HI>Poliphontes</HI>,</L>
<L>'Twill be, to fall for Vengeance.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Soft!&mdash;he <HI>comes</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt Euricles and I&s;men&eacute;.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Wear for a Moment, Heart! the Veil thou hat'&s;t.</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="19" REF="18">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE>MEROPE, POLIPHONTES.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Ever in <HI>Tears</HI>, my Queen! &mdash; now, give a Truce</L>
<L>To Sighs: and ca&s;t a&s;ide your needle&s;s Sorrow.</L>
<L>Shake from tho&s;e injur'd Eyes, a Grief that dims 'em:</L>
<L>And to the Voice of <HI>Love</HI>, vouch&s;afe your Ear.</L>
<L>&mdash;<HI>Mycene's Chiefs</HI> have ta&s;k'd my willing Sword</L>
<L>To <HI>guard</HI>, and (wou'd you &s;mile) <HI>partake</HI>, your Throne.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Unblu&s;hing Faction, What <HI>bold</HI> Brows are Thine!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Faction, uprooted now, &s;urvives no more.</L>
<L>One &s;ole <HI>Divi&s;ion</HI> re&s;ts: &mdash; 'twixt <HI>You</HI>, and <HI>Me</HI>.</L>
<L>La&s;t, let <HI>us</HI>, too, unite&mdash;Peace, Rea&s;on, Safety,</L>
<L>Confed'rate Strength, joint Int're&s;t, All, concur;</L>
<L>To recommend, and firm, this courted Knot</L>
<L>&mdash;You frown&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I do, indeed: and gaze, with Horror!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Gaze on.&mdash;I am no Stranger to <HI>my&s;elf:</HI></L>
<L>Nor to a Woman's <HI>Pa&s;&s;ions</HI>. &mdash; I grew grey</L>
<L>Beneath a Weight, of Winters &s;pent in Arms.</L>
<L>&mdash;I know, Time's Furrows are no Paths to Love.</L>
<L>I know too, <HI>You</HI> are younger: &mdash; &s;till, retain</L>
<L>Charms, pa&s;t their &s;ickly Bloom, and ripe as Summer.</L>
<L>I know it, All&mdash;But, Wi&s;dom knows it <HI>not</HI>.</L>
<L>Intere&s;t of State o'er-leaps nice Ta&s;tes in Love.</L>
<L>&mdash;Weigh not my Offer in Di&s;dain's light Balance.</L>
<L>You are the Daughter, Mother, Wife of <HI>Kings:</HI></L>
<L>But the State wants a <HI>Ma&s;ter</HI>.&mdash;What avails</L>
<L>Vain Title, till &s;ome Sword, like mine, &s;upports it.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Heaven, that o'ercharg'd my Heart with Loads of Woe,</L>
<L>For this new In&s;ult, left it unprepar'd.</L>
<L>Bold <HI>Subject</HI>, of a King who call'd <HI>me</HI> Wife!</L>
<L>Dar'&s;t thou defame the Mem'ry of thy <HI>Lord</HI>,</L>
<L>With &s;uch audacious Hope?&mdash; A&s;pire, to <HI>me!</HI></L>
<L>Me, to &s;upplant my <HI>Child!</HI> my Heart's whole Care:</L>
<L>Stain his di&s;honour'd Throne, with Guilt and Thee!</L>
<L><PB N="20" REF="19"><HI>Me</HI>, can&s;t thou dream &s;o ba&s;e, to wed Thy Lowne&s;s:</L>
<L>And crown with Empire's Wreath a Soldier's Brow?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Soldier?</HI> immortal Gods!&mdash;<HI>Who</HI> more de&s;erves</L>
<L>To <HI>govern</HI>, States, than He who, be&s;t can <HI>&s;ave?</HI></L>
<L>&mdash;With how perver&s;e an Aptitude, Di&s;dain</L>
<L>Forgets, its own Foundation!&mdash;<HI>teach</HI> it, Madam!</L>
<L>That All that &s;wells <HI>your Pride</HI>, &s;upports <HI>my Honour</HI>.</L>
<L>He who was, fir&s;t, call'd <HI>King</HI>, e're That, was <HI>Soldier</HI>.</L>
<L>Great, becau&s;e brave; and &s;cepter'd, by his <HI>Sword</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;Birth is a Shadow. Courage, &s;elf-&s;u&s;tain'd,</L>
<L>Oat-lord's Succe&s;&s;ion's Phlegm &mdash; and needs <HI>no</HI> An|ce&s;tors.</L>
<L>I am <HI>above De&s;cent</HI>; and prize no <HI>Blood</HI>.</L>
<L>Scarce is my own left mine; 'tis lo&s;t, for Glory:</L>
<L>Spilt, in my Country's Cau&s;e: in <HI>Yours</HI>, fair Scorner!</L>
<L>&mdash;Let what &s;till warms my Heart flow, <HI>la&s;t</HI>, for <HI>You</HI>.</L>
<L>Nay, why <HI>averted?</HI>&mdash;Spite of your contempt,</L>
<L><HI>My</HI> Worth weighs <HI>heavie&s;t</HI>, put <HI>but Rank</HI> in Balance.</L>
<L>Take Safety&mdash;'tis <HI>my</HI> Gift. Fill half <HI>my</HI> Throne;</L>
<L>My Party calls <HI>All</HI> mine: Love <HI>&s;hares</HI> it yours</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Party?</HI> Thou fell Provoker, of Reproach!</L>
<L>Party &s;hould tremble, where a <HI>Monarch</HI> rules?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>There will be Parties; and there <HI>mu&s;t</HI> be Kings:</L>
<L>And he, who be&s;t can <HI>curb</HI>, was form'd to reign.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Blu&s;h, if thou can'&s;t, thou Foe to Truth and Fame,</L>
<L>To thy King's A&s;hes, to his Widow's Tears;</L>
<L>To his lo&s;t Son's hard, hopele&s;s, friendle&s;s, Fate:</L>
<L>And his high kindred Gods, who gave him Empire.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Tis doubtful, whether, yet, this Son <HI>&s;urvives</HI>.</L>
<L>But, come he, if he <HI>can</HI>, from Death's dumb Shade,</L>
<L>And, back'd by kindred Gods, reclaim his Throne.</L>
<L>&mdash;I &s;eek not to <HI>deceive</HI> you.&mdash;Stern <HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI>.</L>
<L>Brooks no &s;uch feeble Ma&s;ter. Warlike States</L>
<L>Lean, but on time-try'd Columns, Kings, who&s;e Claim</L>
<L>Springs from their <HI>Souls</HI> &mdash; and who <HI>defend</HI>, and reign.</L>
<L>&mdash;I, who <HI>reveng</HI>'d your Lord, by Right &s;ucceed him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Succeed him, Traitor?&mdash;Has he not a <HI>Son?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Boy-brain'd <HI>Eumenes</HI> is too young, for Power&mdash;</L>
<L>Be Pride his Birth-right&mdash;I'm content with Empire.</L>
<L><PB N="21" REF="20">&mdash;Why &s;hould he, acting nothing, a&s;k for All?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Gods were his Great Forefathers,&mdash;<HI>thence</HI>, his Claim.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Far other Value, bears <HI>Mycen&eacute;'s Crown</HI>.</L>
<L>Right, to rule <HI>Men</HI>, is now no longer held</L>
<L>By dull De&s;cent, like <HI>Land</HI>'s low Heritage:</L>
<L>'Tis the pluck'd Fruit of Toil&mdash;'tis the paid Price</L>
<L>Of Blood lo&s;t nobly: And 'tis, thence, <HI>my</HI> Due.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What ha&s;t thou done, thou Wretch! to dare &s;uch Hope?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Bethink you, of that Day, when the&s;e proud Walls</L>
<L>Blu&s;h'd with the Blood you boa&s;t, from Traitor's Swords.</L>
<L>Review your helple&s;s <HI>Hu&s;band</HI>&mdash;&s;ee your <HI>Sons</HI>,</L>
<L>Expiring, round you.&mdash;Wipe tho&s;e gu&s;hing Eyes&mdash;</L>
<L>And view me, what I <HI>was:</HI> Not, then, too <HI>low</HI></L>
<L>To &s;hare your ruffled <HI>Pa&s;&s;ions</HI>.&mdash;Yes: 'Twas I,</L>
<L>From your freed Palace chas'd th' o'erwhelming Foe:</L>
<L>Sav'd your <HI>Herculean</HI> Sceptre, and its Queen.</L>
<L>&mdash;I, I, <HI>repell'd</HI>,&mdash;the Woes you could but <HI>weep</HI>.</L>
<L>See <HI>there</HI>, my Right, my Rank, my Claim to <HI>Love</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Hear, hear him, Heaven! and give me back my Son.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Yes: Let him come, this <HI>Son!</HI> &mdash; He &s;hall be taught</L>
<L>Le&s;&s;ons of Glory: Taught <HI>my</HI> Arts to reign.</L>
<L>&mdash;<HI>Joy</HI> to the Blood of <HI>Hercules!</HI>&mdash;I, too,</L>
<L>Revere: Let others dread it. <HI>My</HI> Ambition</L>
<L>Climbs, <HI>beyond</HI> Progeny&mdash;not to de&s;cend</L>
<L>From Heaven, <HI>my</HI> Wi&s;h. Could I a&s;pire, to be,</L>
<L>My&s;elf, a God, 'twere well.&mdash;To &s;pring <HI>from</HI> Gods,</L>
<L>Is le&s;s, than mine&mdash;who, <HI>like</HI> a God, <HI>command</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Think</HI> &mdash; e're thou claim'&s;t a Greatne&s;s, <HI>not</HI> thy own&mdash;</L>
<L>If thou would'&s;t emulate a God, be <HI>ju&s;t:</HI></L>
<L><HI>Man</HI> can be <HI>brave</HI>, too boldly.&mdash;<HI>Hercules</HI></L>
<L>Sav'd many a King.&mdash;But, did he <HI>&s;teal</HI> their <HI>Dia|dems?</HI></L>
<L>&mdash;Would'&s;t thou re&s;emble <HI>Hercules?</HI>&mdash;Protect</L>
<L>Unfriended Innocence. A&s;&s;ert thy Prince.</L>
<L><PB N="22" REF="21">Re&s;tore th' unhappy Wand'rer to my Arms;</L>
<L>Cea&s;e to afflict; and <HI>give</HI> him, to my Fondne&s;s.</L>
<L>&mdash;<HI>So</HI>, cou'd thy Influence move, <HI>&s;o</HI> try'd, <HI>&s;o</HI> courted,</L>
<L>Who knows&mdash;for, Gratitude has Power, <HI>like</HI> Love&mdash;</L>
<L>Who knows&mdash;how far I <HI>might</HI> forget my Glory&mdash;</L>
<L>And&mdash;if Peace dwells &s;o low&mdash;<HI>Expect</HI> it <HI>not</HI>&mdash;</L>
<L>I will not bid you hope&mdash;that I <HI>can &s;toop</HI>.</L>
<L>So greatly far.&mdash;<HI>Bend</HI>, I am &s;ure, I <HI>cannot</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Merop&eacute;.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE IV.</HEAD>
<STAGE>POLIPHONTES, EROX.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Erox.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Ent'ring, I heard her too pre&s;umptuous Scorn,</L>
<L>And wonder'd, at your Patience! Waits a King,</L>
<L>For a weak Woman's <HI>Wi&s;h</HI>, to fix his Throne?</L>
<L>Greatly and bravely have you clear'd your Way</L>
<L>To the Hill's Foot: Yet, when it courts your climb|ing,</L>
<L>Fall back, to <HI>&s;igh</HI>; and &s;eek <HI>her</HI> Hand to lead you!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Near, as thou think'&s;t I &s;tand, my warier Eye</L>
<L>Marks, 'twixt the Throne and me, a <HI>Precipice</HI>,</L>
<L>Where Faith or I fall headlong.&mdash;Does not <HI>Merop&eacute;</HI></L>
<L>Know, her <HI>Eumenes near?</HI>&mdash;Shou'd he return,</L>
<L>Th' incon&s;tant People wou'd with Shouts receive him,</L>
<L>And &s;mooth his way to Empire, o'er <HI>my</HI> Bo&s;om.</L>
<L>&mdash;This &s;hou'd I <HI>&s;uffer</HI>&mdash;all in vain my Sword</L>
<L>Succeeded, when <HI>his Father fell, my Victim</HI>.</L>
<L>In vain <HI>bled</HI> both his <HI>Brothers</HI>.&mdash;Vainly, too,</L>
<L>Thy Veil, O &s;ilent Darkne&s;s! has conceal'd me,</L>
<L>Till I, behind <HI>thee</HI>, have been thought th' <HI>Avenger</HI>:</L>
<L>Ev'n of the <HI>Blood I &s;pilt</HI>. &mdash;At length, impends</L>
<L>Th' important Hour&punc; and Fate is <HI>mine</HI>, or <HI>Merop&eacute;</HI>'s.</L>
<L>&mdash;Dear to <HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI>, &s;hould this Son <HI>arrive</HI>,</L>
<L>Where are my fifteen Years long Toils in Blood?</L>
<L><HI>Eumenes mu&s;t not come.</HI>&mdash;Doom'd from his Cradle,</L>
<L>To bla&s;t my thwarted Schemes, <HI>Atonement</HI> claims him.</L>
<L>&mdash;Thou know'&s;t, from Proofs, mo&s;t timely inter|cepted,</L>
<L>This new Boy King <HI>returns</HI>, and hopes <HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI>.</L>
<L><PB N="23" REF="22">What &s;hall we do? Night veils not long (they &s;ay)</L>
<L>The <HI>Murd'rer</HI>'s time-told Secret. Some blind Chance</L>
<L>May whi&s;per, Truths he mu&s;t not live to <HI>hear</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;If, as our Prie&s;ts a&s;&s;ure us, Heaven <HI>loves Vengeance</HI>,</L>
<L>Sure! after fifteen Years, of patient <HI>Stray</HI>,</L>
<L>The leaden-footed Creeper, now, draws <HI>near!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Erox.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Tru&s;t your high Fortune, and di&s;dain a Doubt.</L>
<L>Fore&s;ight and <HI>Fiercene&s;s</HI> are the brave Man's Gods,</L>
<L>And his own Hand &s;upports him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>My late Order?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Erox.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Twas, with a &s;ilent Firmne&s;s, well obey'd.</L>
<L>&mdash;From <HI>Elis</HI> to <HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI>, every Road</L>
<L>Is watch'd, by &s;leeple&s;s Warders.&mdash;If they come,</L>
<L><HI>Narbas</HI> and <HI>He</HI>, their <HI>Gods</HI> mu&s;t march before 'em:</L>
<L>Or not <HI>Alcides'</HI> Blood cou'd &s;cape the &s;hedding.</L>
<L>Your Soldier's Zeal is warm.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>But is it <HI>blind?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Erox.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>It <HI>is</HI>.&mdash;None knows his <HI>Name</HI>, who&s;e Life he waits.</L>
<L>All they have yet been told is, a &s;ad Tale,</L>
<L>Of an <HI>old wily Traitor</HI>, leading with him,</L>
<L>On murd'rous Purpo&s;e, an <HI>A&s;&s;a&s;&s;in Youth</HI>,</L>
<L>Urg'd by exacted Oaths, to &s;eek <HI>your</HI> Death.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>But, what this Rumour, of <HI>Mi&s;anthus kill'd</HI>.</L>
<L>Before <HI>Alcides' Temple?</HI>&mdash;Is that true?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Erox.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Too &s;ure, he fell.&mdash;I cho&s;e <HI>his</HI> tru&s;ty Arm,</L>
<L>Join'd with his martial <HI>Brother</HI>'s, as mo&s;t fit,</L>
<L>To guard that likelie&s;t Station; where, &s;hould <HI>Narbas</HI></L>
<L>Dare, with his Exile, touch <HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI>'s <HI>Border</HI>,</L>
<L>Fir&s;t, they wou'd re&s;t, to beg That <HI>Godhead</HI>'s Care,</L>
<L>From whom their Race pre&s;umes its proud De&s;cent.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Twas Foreca&s;t, worthy of a Zeal, like Thine.</L>
<L>Nor cou'd thy Care have cho&s;en an abler Hand,</L>
<L>Or one more try'd in Blood, than That <HI>Mi&s;anthus</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;'Twas <HI>He</HI>, thou know'&s;t, that, faithful to my Cau&s;e,</L>
<L>On that black Night, attending, near <HI>Cre&s;phontes</HI>,</L>
<L>Taught the King's Sword, amid the Du&s;k of Slaughter,</L>
<L>To pierce its <HI>Ma&s;ter</HI>'s Brea&s;t.&mdash;An Act, &s;o daring,</L>
<L>De&s;erv'd the Sword, tho' three rich <HI>Gems</HI> adorn'd it,</L>
<L>He <HI>had</HI> it: And he <HI>wore</HI> it, for his Pains.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="23">
<SPEAKER><HI>Erox.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Yet, at <HI>Alcides' Temple</HI>, drew it ra&s;hly,</L>
<L>And <HI>lo&s;t it</HI>, with his <HI>Life</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>How <HI>&s;cap'd</HI> his Brother?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Erox.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Scar'd</HI>, out of Mem'ry's U&s;e, All he cou'd tell me</L>
<L>Was, that the God in&s;pir'd &s;ome <HI>dreadful Form!</HI></L>
<L>Some more than mortal <HI>Mon&s;ter</HI>;&mdash;And <HI>He fled</HI>,</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Vile Safety!&mdash;left his Brother unreveng'd:</L>
<L>And &s;hun'd a Soldier's Death.&mdash;We mu&s;t be watchful.</L>
<L>Some in-felt <HI>Bodings</HI> bid me call this Stranger</L>
<L><HI>Eumenes:</HI> Or his <HI>Friend</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Erox.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>That Fear was mine:</L>
<L>Till, on Reflexion that he came, <HI>alone</HI>,</L>
<L>It look'd unlikely &mdash;Chance it, as it may,</L>
<L>Whene'er he this way comes, he comes, to <HI>die</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>True.&mdash;Yet, I cou'd have wi&s;h'd to <HI>&s;pare this</HI> Crime,</L>
<L>But, one fir&s;t cho&s;en, the Re&s;t grow nece&s;&s;ary:</L>
<L>So falls the Son.&mdash;The <HI>Mother</HI> mu&s;t not follow.</L>
<L>Her, I have <HI>Need</HI> of. Marriage mends my Reign.</L>
<L>Her rightful Title con&s;ecrates Ambition:</L>
<L>And U&s;urpation whitens into <HI>Law</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;The People love her: I, po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ing <HI>her</HI>,</L>
<L>Hold her Friends too, in <HI>Dowry.&mdash;Erox!</HI>&mdash;thou,</L>
<L>Who&s;e Fate grows clo&s;e to mine, a&s;&s;i&s;t my Scheme.</L>
<L>Skill'd how to &s;pread Craft's Nets, allure the People.</L>
<L>Train 'em, by ev'ry Art: poize ev'ry Temper,</L>
<L>Avarice will <HI>&s;ell</HI> his <HI>Soul:</HI> Buy That, and <HI>mould</HI> it.</L>
<L>Weakne&s;s will be <HI>deluded</HI>; there, grow <HI>eloquent</HI>.</L>
<L>Is there a tott'ring Faith? Grapple it fa&s;t</L>
<L>By <HI>Flatt'ry:</HI> And profu&s;ely deal <HI>my Favours</HI>.</L>
<L><HI>Threaten</HI> the Guilty. <HI>Entertain</HI> the Gay.</L>
<L><HI>Frighten</HI> the Rich. Find <HI>Wi&s;hes</HI>, for the Wanton:</L>
<L>And <HI>Reverence</HI>, for the Godly,&mdash;Let none '&s;cape thee.</L>
<L>Dive into <HI>Hearts:</HI> Sound every Nature's <HI>Bia&s;s</HI>&mdash;</L>
<L>And bribe Men by their <HI>Pa&s;&s;ions</HI>.&mdash;But, The&s;e Arts,</L>
<L>Already Thine, why wa&s;te I Time to <HI>teach</HI> thee!</L>
<L>Vainly, the <HI>Sword</HI> &s;ucce&s;sful &s;cales a Throne;</L>
<L>Since, Fortune <HI>changing</HI>, Strength's lo&s;t Hope is flown.</L>
<L>But <HI>Art</HI>, call'd in, attracts reluctant <HI>Will:</HI></L>
<L>And, what were lo&s;t by Power, is gain'd by Skill.</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB REF="24">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The Palace.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>MEROPE. EURICLES. ISMENE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MEROPE.</SPEAKER>
<L>IS the World dumb, on my <HI>Eumene</HI>'s Fate?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Calamity, too &s;oon, had found a Tongue.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Has Nothing, from the Borders, yet been heard?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Nothing, that claims <HI>your</HI> notice.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Who is <HI>He</HI>,</L>
<L>This Pri&s;oner, I am told, but now, brought guarded?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>A ra&s;h young Stranger, caught with guilty Hand,</L>
<L>Red, from the recent Marks of &s;ome late Murder.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>A <HI>Murder!</HI> an <HI>unknown!</HI> &mdash; WHOM, has he kill'd?</L>
<L><HI>How?</HI> and <HI>where</HI>, was it?&mdash;I am fill'd with Horror.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! Sen&s;e too lively, of maternal Love!</L>
<L>All Things alarm your Tenderne&s;s. You hear</L>
<L>Chance &s;peak: and take her Voice, for That of Nature.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>This low Adventure, of &s;ome common Murd'rer,</L>
<L>Some Robber of the Borders, carries with it</L>
<L>No Con&s;equence, of Quality to move you.</L>
<L>This, but one Crime, of many a thou&s;and, frequent</L>
<L>On all our Frontiers: the &s;ad Fruit, of <HI>Wars</HI>,</L>
<L>Dome&s;tic and licentious; weak'ning Ju&s;tice,</L>
<L>And, fearle&s;s in the Face of Heaven, oppo&s;ing</L>
<L>Friend again&s;t Friend, and Brother murd'ring Brother.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What is his <HI>Name?</HI> whence <HI>came</HI> he?&mdash;Why <HI>unknown?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>He &s;eems, and is, if Truth may tru&s;t Appearance,</L>
<L>A Youth of rural Birth,&mdash;Some Nymph'<HI>s Adonis</HI>,</L>
<L>Who&s;e Eye wou'd &s;ooner kill th' unpity'd <HI>Maid</HI>,</L>
<L>Than his unpractis'd <HI>Sword</HI> attempt the <HI>Man</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="26" REF="25">
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Whom (<HI>tell</HI> me) has he <HI>kill'd?</HI> &mdash; an&s;wer. &mdash;</L>
<L>I'll <HI>&s;ee</HI> him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What &s;trange Emotion, This &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>No Matter. &mdash; Bring him.</L>
<L>If I di&s;cover Guilt, 'tis mine to <HI>puni&s;h:</HI></L>
<L>If wrong'd, I owe him <HI>Mercy</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>&mdash; <HI>Should</HI> he have Merit,</L>
<L>'Tis plac'd &s;o low, by Fortune &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Fortune's Faults,</L>
<L>Where Merit &s;uffers, call on Kings, to <HI>mend</HI> 'em.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What can a Wretch like This <HI>de&s;erve</HI> from Power?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>O, <HI>Euricles!</HI> look <HI>inward:</HI> ask thy Heart.</L>
<L><HI>Be</HI>, for a Moment, but, This Wretch, <HI>Thy&s;elf</HI> &mdash;</L>
<L>And, <HI>then</HI>, acquit the Power, that &s;corn'd to note thee.</L>
<L>&mdash; Be&s;ides, who knows? he may &mdash; be <HI>&s;till</HI>, prompt Fear.</L>
<L>Perhaps, my troubled Mind &s;tarts Hints too lightly.</L>
<L>Hearts that have Everything to fear, &s;light Nothing.</L>
<L>&mdash; Let him be brought. &mdash; I will, my&s;elf, examine him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Your Will <HI>mu&s;t</HI> be obey'd.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Go, my <HI>I&s;mene!</HI></L>
<L>Bid tho&s;e who guard the Pris'ner bring him hither.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> I&s;mene.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Be That <HI>my</HI> fitter Task &mdash;
<STAGE><HI>Offering to go.</HI></STAGE></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>No, <HI>Euricles</HI>.</L>
<L>Stay: and partake more Terrors&mdash;Could you think it?</L>
<L>Pre&s;s'd by new Sorrows, I forget my pa&s;t,</L>
<L>And have not yet inform'd you &mdash; <HI>Poliphontes</HI></L>
<L>Has dar'd demand my <HI>Hand:</HI> dar'd &mdash; talk of <HI>Mar|riage</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Great, even beyond their <HI>Seemings</HI>, are your Dangers!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Dangers? &mdash; No Danger, &s;ure! can licen&s;e <HI>That!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Might Freedom be forgiven. &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Be plain.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! Queen!</L>
<L>I know his Offer <HI>In&s;ult:</HI> know, It &s;tains</L>
<L>Your Name. Yet, blu&s;hing, <HI>add</HI>, &mdash; Your forc'd Con|&s;ent,</L>
<L><PB N="27" REF="26">Grown infamou&s;ly <HI>nece&s;&s;ary</HI>, &mdash; &s;tands,</L>
<L>The &s;ole, &s;afe Bar, 'twixt All your Race, and <HI>Ruin</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Tis Horror, but to <HI>think</HI>, &s;o vile a Dream!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>So thinks the <HI>Army</HI>. &mdash; So, the <HI>Senate</HI> thinks.</L>
<L>So, think th'exacting <HI>Gods:</HI> &mdash; and, &s;o &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>The <HI>Gods!</HI></L>
<L>Why are <HI>They</HI> nam'd? &mdash; Could they forgive &s;uch <HI>Fall?</HI></L>
<L>From their own Offspring, to a Son of Clay!</L>
<L>A Birth of Tumult! a blown Bubble, rais'd</L>
<L>By Fortune's Breath; and puff'd above the World,</L>
<L>To &s;hine, a Moment, and go out in Weeping.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>The King, your Son &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Ah! Name not <HI>Him</HI>. &mdash; How, <HI>Euricles!</HI></L>
<L>How would He thank my Choice of <HI>&s;uch</HI> a Father?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Princes grow wi&s;e by Sorrows. He will &s;ee</L>
<L>That hated Choice the Root of all his Safety.</L>
<L>He will, by-That, &s;urvive his menac'd Doom:</L>
<L>Owe his &s;ecur'd Succe&s;&s;ion, to That Act</L>
<L>Of dire Nece&s;&s;ity: and thank your Pity.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What, what, have you been telling me?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Hard Truths:</L>
<L>Due, from firm Loyalty, to weak Di&s;tre&s;s.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Can <HI>Euricles</HI> then plead, for <HI>Poliphontes!</HI></L>
<L>You, who have painted him &s;o vile, &s;o truly,</L>
<L>And never &s;toop'd, your&s;elf, from Faith to Fraud?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I know him guilty: &mdash; but, I know him <HI>ra&s;h:</HI></L>
<L>Know him <HI>re&s;i&s;tle&s;s:</HI> know him <HI>childle&s;s</HI>, too;</L>
<L>And know, you love <HI>Eumenes</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Loving <HI>Him</HI>,</L>
<L>How can I chu&s;e but <HI>hate</HI>, the Hand that wrongs him?</L>
<L>&mdash; Leave <HI>Poliphontes</HI> odious: nor, forever,</L>
<L>Dwell thus on Claims of <HI>Policy</HI>; &mdash; forgetful,</L>
<L>That Princes are <HI>above</HI> the&s;e Self-&s;ecurings:</L>
<L>And born, to live for Truth &mdash; or die for Glory.</L>
<L>&mdash; Speak to me of my <HI>Son:</HI> Say what you know</L>
<L>Of him. &mdash; hide Nothing &mdash; for, &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Sits and weeps, regardle&s;s of</HI> Eumenes<HI>'s Entrance</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Behold! &mdash; the Stranger,</L>
<L>You long'd, a Moment &s;ince, to &s;ee, and que&s;tion:</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="28" REF="27">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>MEROPE, EURICLES, ISMENE, <HI>Guards with</HI> EUMENES <HI>in Chains</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE>[<HI>To</HI> I&s;mene]</STAGE>
Is that the <HI>Queen</HI>, &s;o fam'd for Mi&s;eries?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>It <HI>is</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>How &s;weetly aweful! &mdash; how <HI>adorn'd</HI> by Sor|rows!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Why do&s;t thou pau&s;e? the Queen admits thee nearer.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>No wonder, &s;o much Sweetne&s;s, <HI>&s;o di&s;tre&s;s'd</HI>.</L>
<L>Mov'd, even &s;o greatly di&s;tant, &mdash; as to <HI>me:</HI></L>
<L>And drew me from my De&s;art! &mdash; Give me Leave</L>
<L>To &s;tand, a while &mdash; and gaze unmark'd &mdash; and <HI>note</HI> her.</L>
<L>&mdash; O, ye protecting <HI>Gods!</HI> whate'er becomes</L>
<L>Of an abandon'd, namele&s;s Thing, like <HI>me</HI>,</L>
<L>Ble&s;s this <HI>Supreme</HI> Unfortunate! this Face,</L>
<L>That, awefully &s;ublime, amid&s;t Di&s;tre&s;s,</L>
<L>Glows warm, with weeping Mercy! &mdash; Bold Adver|&s;ity,</L>
<L>That &s;trikes &agrave;t Crowns, demands, O Heaven! <HI>Thy</HI> guarding.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Madam! &mdash; the <HI>Pri&s;oner</HI> waits.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE>[<HI>Turning to ob&s;erve him</HI>]</STAGE>
A <HI>Murderer</HI>, This! &mdash;</L>
<L>Why &s;tands he di&s;tant thus? &mdash; Come forward Stran|ger.</L>
<L>&mdash; A Mein like this, a Murd'rer's! &mdash; <HI>Can</HI> it be,</L>
<L>That Looks, &s;o form'd for Truth, &s;o mark'd for Inno|cence,</L>
<L>Cover a cruel Heart? &mdash; Come <HI>nearer</HI>, Youth!</L>
<L>Thou art unhappy; bid That Fate <HI>protect</HI> thee:</L>
<L>And &s;peak, as to an Ear that loves the Wretched.</L>
<L>An&s;wer me now. &mdash;Who&s;e was the Blood thou &s;hed'&s;t?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh, Queen! &mdash;Yet &mdash; for a Moment &mdash; &s;pare my Tongue.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Murder, and <HI>Mode&s;ty!</HI>&mdash;Whence, all this Shame?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Re&s;pect, Confu&s;ion, &mdash; &s;omething, <HI>here</HI> &mdash; <HI>un-nam'd</HI>,</L>
<L><PB N="29" REF="28">And never felt, till <HI>now</HI>, &mdash; have bound my Tongue.</L>
<L>But &mdash; oh! do Ju&s;tice, to your Power to &s;hake me;</L>
<L>And, let not <HI>He&s;itation</HI> &mdash; pa&s;s &mdash; for <HI>Guilt</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Go on. &mdash; Who was he, whom, I'm told, thou ha&s;t kill'd?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>One, who with Wrongs, and In&s;ult, fir'd my Ra&s;hne&s;s.</L>
<L>One, who was Young, like <HI>me</HI>; but, &s;ure, le&s;s <HI>hone&s;t</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Young!</HI> &mdash; was he young? &mdash; &s;peak; <HI>tell</HI> me.</L>
<L>&mdash; No &mdash; be <HI>dumb</HI>.</L>
<L>Ice, at my con&s;cious Heart, were <HI>warm</HI> &mdash; compar'd</L>
<L>With what he chills my Soul with! &mdash; Did&s;t thou <HI>know</HI> him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I did <HI>not</HI>. All <HI>Mycene</HI>'s Earth, and Air,</L>
<L>Her Cities, and her Sons, are new, to <HI>me</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What, was he <HI>arm'd</HI>, this young A&s;&s;aulter? came he</L>
<L>With <HI>Malice?</HI> or for <HI>Robbery?</HI> Be of Comfort.</L>
<L>If he attack'd thee, thy Defence was nece&s;&s;ary,</L>
<L>And &s;ad Nece&s;&s;ity makes All things ju&s;t.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Heaven is my Witne&s;s, I provok'd him not.</L>
<L>'Tis not in Valour's Wi&s;h, to <HI>offer</HI> In&s;ult:</L>
<L>And &s;ure! it is no <HI>Crime</HI>, to check it, <HI>offer'd</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>On, then &mdash; relate the Chance, that led thee hi|ther.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Entring your Borders, I beheld a <HI>Temple</HI>,</L>
<L>Sacred to <HI>Hercules</HI>; the God, my Soul,</L>
<L>Low as my Lot was ca&s;t, <HI>a&s;pires</HI> to Honour.</L>
<L>&mdash; What &s;hould I do? bare Vot'ry as I was!</L>
<L>I had <HI>no Off'rings:</HI> brought no <HI>Victims</HI> with me.</L>
<L>Poor, and oppre&s;s'd by Fortune, what I <HI>could</HI>,</L>
<L>I <HI>gave</HI> &mdash; I knelt, and pour'd a <HI>Heart</HI> before him,</L>
<L>Warm as a hundred Hecatombs! pure, pridele&s;s,</L>
<L>Pious, and firm. &mdash;Th'Unhappy <HI>can</HI> no more.</L>
<L>&mdash; Yet, humbly con&s;cious of my far-thrown Di&s;tance,</L>
<L>I ask'd not, for <HI>my&s;elf</HI>, his undue Ble&s;&s;ing.</L>
<L>I pray'd Protection, to his <HI>own</HI> high Race:</L>
<L>For, I had <HI>heard</HI>, Great Queen! your wrongs <HI>re|quir'd</HI> it.</L>
<L>The <HI>Pre&s;ent God</HI>, methought, <HI>receiv'd</HI> my Prayer.</L>
<L>His Altar trembled; and his Temple rung!</L>
<L><PB N="30" REF="29">Keen, undulating, Glories beam'd about me:</L>
<L>I know not how I <HI>bore</HI> it! &mdash; but, my Heart,</L>
<L>Full of the Force infus'd, at once grew <HI>Va&s;ter</HI>.</L>
<L>My &s;welling Courage, far <HI>above my&s;elf</HI>,</L>
<L>Inflam'd me: &mdash; and I <HI>glow'd</HI>, with all the <HI>God</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE>[<HI>Ri&s;ing in Emotion.</HI>]</STAGE>
Speak on. Methinks, the</L>
<L>God thou nam'&s;t &s;peaks <HI>in</HI> thee!</L>
<L>End Ev'ry <HI>Hearer</HI> glows, as warm'd as Thou!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I bow'd, and left the Temple &mdash; Following, came</L>
<L>Two Men, of haughty Stride, with angry Lowre:</L>
<L>Roughly, acco&s;ting, they reproach'd my Prayer.</L>
<L>How did I dare, they ask'd, &s;olicite Heaven,</L>
<L>To aid Sedition's Purpo&s;es? No God</L>
<L>Should <HI>&s;ave</HI> a Wretch like me, pre&s;crib'd by Power.</L>
<L>&mdash; I heard, a&s;toni&s;h'd; and prepar'd to &s;peak:</L>
<L>When, with impatient Fiercene&s;s, Each rais'd Arm,</L>
<L>With Rage conjoin'd, came on.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE>[<HI>Interrupting.</HI>]</STAGE>
Both! &mdash;Came they, <HI>Both</HI>,</L>
<L>To wound thee? &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Both, with more than Madman's Frenzy,</L>
<L>Struck at my Brea&s;t ignobly.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Thou ha&s;t eas'd me.</L>
<L>Go on. &mdash;The&s;e Men had Souls, that match'd their Fate.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Un-arm'd, and inoffen&s;ive, &s;o &s;urpriz'd,</L>
<L>The God I had addre&s;s'd <HI>repaid</HI> my Prayer.</L>
<L>&mdash; Warding the weake&s;t Stroke, with Swordle&s;s Hand,</L>
<L>Fiercely I clos'd, and &s;eiz'd the wre&s;ted Steel</L>
<L>From Him who&s;e &s;tronger Arm more nearly pre&s;s'd me.</L>
<L>Seiz'd it with Light'ning's Swiftne&s;s: for, Di&s;tre&s;s</L>
<L>Row&s;es the <HI>weak</HI> to Vengeance. &mdash;On Him&s;elf,</L>
<L>I turn'd his pointed Weapon: &s;av'd <HI>my</HI> Brea&s;t,</L>
<L>And plung'd it in his own. &mdash; He fell. &mdash;. The Other</L>
<L>Started, and curs'd: but, like a Coward, <HI>fled</HI>,</L>
<L>Fal&s;e to his dying Fellow. &mdash; Mighty Queen,</L>
<L>This is the &s;ad &s;hort Truth. May the kind Power</L>
<L>I bow'd to touch your Ear; and move your Pity!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>She were a Tygre&s;s, that could hear this Tale,</L>
<L>And pau&s;e, upon thy Pardon. &mdash; Still, go on:</L>
<L>How wert thou &s;eiz'd? hide Nothing, and hope All.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Shock'd by uncertain Dread for what was done,</L>
<L>And ignorant <HI>Who&s;e</HI> the Blood; which, looking down,</L>
<L><PB N="31" REF="30">I &s;aw, gu&s;h wide, and &s;tain th' incircling Sand;</L>
<L>I gaz'd a&s;toni&s;h'd round: and mark'd, beneath,</L>
<L>Where, at a Furlong's Di&s;tance, the Salt wave</L>
<L>Broke on the pebbly &s;hore with mournful Murmur.</L>
<L>Sudden I &s;natch'd the Corps, from where it bled:</L>
<L>And, ha&s;t'ning to the Beach, with <HI>added Weight</HI>,</L>
<L>(Appealing <HI>Neptune</HI>,) gave it to the <HI>Sea</HI>.</L>
<L>That done, I &s;igh'd, and fled: Your Guards, great Queen,</L>
<L>For what e&s;capes &s;uch Eyes, as <HI>Heaven</HI>'s, and <HI>Yours!</HI></L>
<L>Un&s;een by me, mark'd all; follow'd, and took me.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>&mdash;<HI>To</HI> Euricles.</L>
<L>Did he <HI>re&s;i&s;t</HI>, when &s;eiz'd?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I <HI>cou'd not</HI>, Madam.</L>
<L>The Name of <HI>Merop&eacute;</HI> di&s;arm'd my <HI>Will</HI>.</L>
<L>They told me they were Yours. I how'd, and yielded.</L>
<L>Gave 'em my new-gain'd <HI>Sword</HI>: and took their <HI>Chains</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>This Youth, by Him he kill'd, was judg'd <HI>Another</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! I have noted All: and Heaven was <HI>ju&s;t</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash; Retire, to farther Di&s;tance, gentle Youth.&mdash;</L>
<L>'Tis well. Wait, there, my Call&mdash;I'll tell thee, <HI>Euricles!</HI></L>
<L>Methought, at every Word this Wanderer &s;poke,</L>
<L>Pity&mdash;or Something, <HI>tenderer</HI> than Pity,</L>
<L>Clung to my aking Heart&s;trings! nay, 'twas <HI>&s;tranger!</HI></L>
<L>For, I will tell thee All.&mdash;<HI>Cre&s;phontes'</HI> Features,</L>
<L>My dear dead manly <HI>Lord</HI>'s re&s;embled Features;</L>
<L>I &s;aw, and trac'd, (I blu&s;h, to think what Folly!)</L>
<L>Trac'd,&mdash;in this Cottage Hero's hone&s;t Face.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Compa&s;&s;ion is a kind and generous Painter.</L>
<L>&mdash;Yet, Truth Her&s;elf mu&s;t grow as <HI>blind</HI>, as Fortune,</L>
<L>Ere &s;he cou'd look on That unhappy Youth;</L>
<L>And find him <HI>le&s;s</HI>, than worth her kinde&s;t Pity.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>I&s;mene</HI> &s;peaks <HI>my</HI> Thoughts. He's innocent.</L>
<L>The Gods have &s;tamp'd their Mark of Candor on him,</L>
<L>And no <HI>Impo&s;tor's Art</HI> inhabits there.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>To</HI> Eumenes.</L>
<L>Again, approach me&mdash;In what Part of <HI>Greece</HI></L>
<L>Did it plea&s;e Heaven to give thee Birth, good Youth?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>Advancing.</HI></STAGE>
In <HI>Elis</HI>, generous Queen.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>In <HI>Elis</HI>. &mdash; Tell me.</L>
<L>I hop'd, it had been nearer.&mdash;Ha&s;t thou, ever,</L>
<L><PB N="32" REF="31">In thy low Conver&s;e, heard the Swains, thy Neighbours,</L>
<L>Mention a Name, like <HI>Narbas?</HI>&mdash;or <HI>Eumenes?</HI>&mdash;</L>
<L>&mdash;The La&s;t, thou <HI>mu&s;t</HI> have heard of.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Never, Madam.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Never?&mdash;That's <HI>&s;trange!</HI> what then was thy Condition?</L>
<L>What thy Employment? and thy Father's Name?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>My Father was a <HI>Shepherd:</HI> learn'd, and wi&s;e;</L>
<L>Too humble, for Di&s;tinction&mdash;had not Virtue</L>
<L><HI>Compell'd</HI> him, into Notice.&mdash;Shunning Prai&s;e,</L>
<L>He &s;ought Felicity, in &s;ilent Search</L>
<L>Of un-endang'ring Worth, and <HI>infelt</HI> Greatne&s;s.</L>
<L>He liv'd un-envied: for, excelling All,</L>
<L>He veil'd &s;uperior Eminence, by <HI>Mode&s;ty</HI>.</L>
<L>And made Subjection <HI>Sweet</HI>, by Power's Humility.</L>
<L>No claim'd Exemption eas'd his Life from <HI>Care:</HI></L>
<L>Peacefully poor! and reverently belov'd!</L>
<L>His fleecy Harve&s;ts fed him:&mdash;and, his Name</L>
<L>Was <HI>Policletes</HI>, Madam.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What Thy <HI>Own?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Low, like my pa&s;t'ral Care&mdash;to Cottage Ears</L>
<L>Adapted&mdash;and unform'd for <HI>Queen</HI>'s Regard.</L>
<L>&mdash;Yet, <HI>Elis</HI>, oft, will deign to &s;peak of&mdash;<HI>Dorilas</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(A&s;ide.)</HI></STAGE>
Oh! I have lo&s;t my Hope. Heaven mocks Relief:</L>
<L>And every &s;tarting Spark is quench'd in Darkne&s;s.</L>
<L>So, then, your Parents held no <HI>Rank</HI> in <HI>Elis?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Did Place draw Claim from Goodne&s;s they had held</L>
<L>Preferment, with the Highe&s;t&mdash;But their <HI>Virtues</HI>,</L>
<L>Left Room for <HI>no</HI> Enlargement.&mdash;<HI>Native</HI> Eminence</L>
<L><HI>Borrows</HI> no Rank from <HI>Title</HI>&mdash;but <HI>lends</HI> All,</L>
<L>That keeps <HI>Contempt</HI> from Greatne&s;s.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Every Word</L>
<L>He utters has a Charm!&mdash;But, <HI>Why</HI>, at home</L>
<L>So ble&s;s'd, and, to <HI>&s;uch</HI> Parents, doubly dear,</L>
<L>Did&s;t thou, forgetful of the Care thou owd'&s;t 'em,</L>
<L>Quit their kind <HI>Cott</HI>, and leave 'em to their <HI>Tears?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>A vain De&s;ire of <HI>Glory</HI>, fir&s;t, &s;educ'd me.</L>
<L>Oft had I heard my Father mourn <HI>Mycene</HI>,</L>
<L>Weep, for her Civil Wars, and &s;uff'ring <HI>Queen</HI>.</L>
<L><PB N="33" REF="32">Oft, had he charm'd my young, a&s;piring, Soul,</L>
<L>With Wonder, at your Firmne&s;s!&mdash;So, inflam'd,</L>
<L>I learnt, by &s;low Degrees, to think &s;trong <HI>Youth</HI></L>
<L><HI>Di&s;grac'd</HI>, by home-felt Virtues: Weigh'd the Call</L>
<L>Of Glory, again&s;t <HI>Duty</HI>; and grew bold</L>
<L>To hope, <HI>my</HI> humble Arm might add &s;ome Help,</L>
<L>To prop your warring Standards &mdash;See! great Queen,</L>
<L>The &s;ole <HI>Seduction</HI>, of my erring Ra&s;hne&s;s.</L>
<L>For, Heaven has taught me, tho' It loves <HI>your</HI> Cau&s;e,</L>
<L>I merit my Di&s;tre&s;s: who left my Father,</L>
<L>Wanting, perhaps, in Age's feeble Calls,</L>
<L>Some Aids, I might have lent him.&mdash;'Twas a Fault.</L>
<L>But, 'twas my <HI>fir&s;t:</HI> And I may live, to mend it.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>a&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>
Methinks, I hear <HI>Eumenes</HI>&mdash;So, my Soul</L>
<L>Informs me, had <HI>He</HI> known De&s;cent, thus lowly,</L>
<L>So, <HI>My Eumenes</HI> wou'd have thought, and &s;poke.</L>
<L>&mdash;Such, is his Age, where'er conceal'd he mourns:</L>
<L>Perhaps too, &s;uch his Fortune&mdash;driven, like <HI>This</HI>,</L>
<L>From Realm to Realm, a Wand'rer, thus unknown!</L>
<L>Friendle&s;s, and hopele&s;s, and expos'd to Poverty!</L>
<L>&mdash;Oh! what Compa&s;&s;ion will not Woes we &s;uffer</L>
<L>In&s;pire, for <HI>Other's</HI> Sufferings!&mdash;Too &s;ecure,</L>
<L>Thou &s;tand'&s;t, unfeeling Pride! and look'&s;t not round thee.</L>
<L>&mdash;I will have Pity, on this Youth's Di&s;tre&s;s:</L>
<L>And cultivate his Fortune.&mdash;What bold Noi&s;e?</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Shouts heard without.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Whence can &s;uch Rudene&s;s flow!&mdash; Look out,</L>
<L><HI>I&s;mene</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>at a Window.</HI></STAGE>
All Ills are <HI>Poliphontes</HI>. The vile Rabble</L>
<L>Shout their &s;ure Vote, for Trea&s;on. <HI>Poliphontes</HI></L>
<L>Is <HI>King</HI>, proclaim'd,&mdash;and Hope is now no more.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Tis the <HI>la&s;t</HI> Evil.&mdash;Faith <HI>may</HI>, &s;till, find Friends.</L>
<L><HI>All</HI> grow not giddy, when the Public <HI>reels</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! for the <HI>Sword</HI>, once more, your Guards took from me!</L>
<L>Now, now, I <HI>feel</HI> the&s;e Chains: Now, fir&s;t, they <HI>bind</HI> me.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Give</HI> him his Sword. Let him be free, as Air.</L>
<L>Hone&s;t Propo&s;er!&mdash;but, <HI>Thy</HI> Help's too weak,</L>
<L>To prop a Throne, in Danger.&mdash;Wait, without,</L>
<L>Till this kind Lord conducts thee into Safety.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="34" REF="33">
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>O, Queen!&mdash;<HI>forgive</HI> Pre&s;umption, in the <HI>Poor</HI>,</L>
<L>When <HI>They</HI> dare pity Greatne&s;s.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Thou</HI> art Great;</L>
<L>By <HI>Nature</HI>'s Gift:&mdash;or, le&s;s than low, by <HI>Art</HI>'s!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>All have their Mis'ries&punc;&mdash;but, when <HI>Crowns</HI> grow wretched,</L>
<L>'Tis Impudence, in <HI>mean</HI> ones, to complain.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Eumenes.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Too fatally, I prophe&s;ied.&mdash;Confe&s;s</L>
<L>This hard Nece&s;&s;ity: which, now, you find;</L>
<L>And <HI>&s;eem</HI>, at lea&s;t, to &s;ooth the Tyrant's Hope.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I mi&s;conceiv'd the Gods. I dur&s;t not dream,</L>
<L>They cou'd have bid Guilt thrive: and given up <HI>Virtue</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>They <HI>will not</HI>, Madam.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>So, my &s;ad Heart, &s;till,</L>
<L>Struggles to hope: and, if they mark my <HI>Woe</HI>,</L>
<L>They will forgive my <HI>Ra&s;hne&s;s</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Come, what mu&s;t!</L>
<L>I will a&s;&s;emble round you the few faithful,</L>
<L>And, failing to protect, partake your Fall.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Euricles.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE>MEROPE, ISMENE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>O, People! People! They, who tru&s;t your Faith,</L>
<L>Bid the wild Winds blow con&s;tant.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Tis their Love,</L>
<L>Their ill-judg'd Tenderne&s;s, not Lightne&s;s, wrongs you.</L>
<L>They weigh your late-pa&s;t Dangers, dread Renewal:</L>
<L>And wou'd &s;ecure, by this bold <HI>Partner</HI>'s Share,</L>
<L>Your nobler, in the Crown, His Power protects.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>In&s;olent Care!&mdash;&s;hall Subjects to my Son</L>
<L>Wed me to In&s;ult!&mdash;to the Hand I <HI>hate!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>They call the <HI>People</HI>'s Voice, the Voice of Gods.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What villain Ba&s;ene&s;s wants &s;ome bold Pretence</L>
<L>That drags in <HI>Heaven</HI>, to grace it? Thefts, Plots, Per|juries,</L>
<L><PB N="35" REF="34">Avarice, Revenge, the bloody Zeal, of <HI>Pride</HI>,</L>
<L>And unforgiving Bitterne&s;s of Heart;</L>
<L><HI>All</HI>,&mdash;have their Gods to friend! their Prie&s;ts, to &s;anctify.</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE IV.</HEAD>
<STAGE>MEROPE, ISMENE, EURICLES, <HI>with a Sword</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Sorrows on Sorrows bear down Hope's la&s;t Prop.</L>
<L>Now, be a Queen, indeed!&mdash;arm your great Heart,</L>
<L>With Preparation, to its utmo&s;t Stretch:</L>
<L>&mdash;For, if it &s;tands <HI>this</HI> Shock, its Power's immortal.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>No&mdash;I am &s;inking, from all <HI>Sen&s;e</HI> of Pain;</L>
<L>And &s;hall grow <HI>&s;afe</HI>, by Want of Strength to &s;uffer.</L>
<L>Speak.&mdash;there is now but one &s;ad Truth to dread:</L>
<L>And my Soul waits it heard;&mdash;then, re&s;ts, for ever.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>It has pleas'd Heaven&mdash; this <HI>Sword!</HI> this fatal <HI>Sword!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I under&s;tand thee; thou woud'&s;t &s;ay, he's <HI>dead</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! 'tis too &s;urely &s;o: th' atrocious Crime</L>
<L>At la&s;t, &s;ucceeded&mdash;and all Care is vain.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Gods! Gods!&mdash;'tis done.&mdash;And all your Bolts have &s;truck me.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Guard her di&s;tracted Brain!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Save her, kind Heaven!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Where</HI> have I been?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Alas! where Grief, too often,</L>
<L>Has lodg'd, and left, th' Unhappy. &mdash;recollect.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! <HI>Euricles:</HI> I recollect, too much.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Forget it&mdash; for a few &s;hort Moment's Re&s;pite.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Tru&s;t my &s;u&s;taining Heart. It breaks not, <HI>yet</HI>.</L>
<L>Comfort's brief Cloud, methought, came &s;hadowing o'er me.</L>
<L>But I am <HI>found</HI>, again: a Wretch, &s;o friendle&s;s,</L>
<L>That <HI>Madne&s;s</HI> will not lend Relief: but <HI>&s;huns</HI> me.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Peri&s;h, That young, that impious Hypocrite!</L>
<L>That ill-admir'd Attracter of your Pity:</L>
<L>Whom your Protection &s;par'd&mdash;for fancied Virtue!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Who?&mdash;What?&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Not Dorilas?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Him, Him</HI>, That <HI>Dorilas</HI>?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Mon&s;ter! beyond all credit of Deceit!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="36" REF="35">
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>He!</HI>&mdash;'tis impo&s;&s;ible.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>He</HI> was the Murderer.</L>
<L>I bring too clear a Proof. Pa&s;&s;ing, but now,</L>
<L>I found him waiting: freed him from his Chains;</L>
<L>And, to re-arm him, for the Cau&s;e he cho&s;e;</L>
<L>Call'd for his <HI>Sword</HI>&mdash;Which, as he &s;tretch'd his Hand</L>
<L>To take, I mark'd, and trembled at the View,</L>
<L>The&s;e once-known <HI>Gems</HI>&mdash;too well remember'd, <HI>here!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>&mdash; <HI>taking the Sword</HI>.</L>
<L>Oh, All ye &s;leeping Gods! 'twas My <HI>Cre&s;phontes!</HI></L>
<L>'Twas the <HI>King</HI>'s Sword. <HI>Narbas</HI>, beyond all Doubting,</L>
<L>Sav'd it, that dreadful Night, for my <HI>Eumenes</HI>.</L>
<L>Oh! what a fal&s;e vile Tale has this taught Fury,</L>
<L>This practis'd, art-accompli&s;h'd, Flatterer form'd,</L>
<L>To cheat us into Pardon!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Heaven be&s;t knows,</L>
<L>What <HI>Number</HI> of A&s;&s;ociate Villains <HI>join'd</HI>,</L>
<L>To perpetrate this Crime! for, ah! too &s;ure,</L>
<L>No &s;ingle Murd'rer's Hand had Force to <HI>dare</HI>,</L>
<L>Far le&s;s to triumph o'er, a Prince like ours.</L>
<L>No Blood of <HI>Hercules</HI> is &s;hed &s;o tamely.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Take the dumb dreadful Witne&s;s from my Sight.</L>
<STAGE><HI>giving</HI> Euricles <HI>the Sword</HI>.</STAGE>
<L>Yet, &s;tay.&mdash;return it me.&mdash;</L>
<STAGE><HI>re&s;umes the Sword&mdash;and kneels.</HI></STAGE>
<L>I <HI>thank</HI> ye&mdash;Gods!</L>
<L>Thank your in&s;piring Ju&s;tice: and <HI>accept</HI> it.</L>
<L>Live, <HI>but</HI> to thank you,&mdash;for this dire, due, Sacrifice;</L>
<L>Which, from the childle&s;s Mother's widow'd Hand,</L>
<L>Your Heav'n-directed Vengeance well <HI>demands</HI>.</L>
<STAGE><HI>&s;he ri&s;es.</HI></STAGE>
<L>Yes. I will <HI>&s;heathe</HI> it, on my Hu&s;band's <HI>Tomb</HI>,</L>
<L>Deep, in the <HI>bleeding Murd'rer</HI>'s panting Heart;</L>
<L>Then, &s;corning <HI>Poliphontes</HI>, pierce my <HI>own</HI>;</L>
<L>So, die, reveng'd, and &s;afe,&mdash;<HI>ab&s;olving</HI> Heaven.</L>
<L>&mdash;Go, <HI>Euricles</HI> &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Not <HI>&s;o</HI>.&mdash;Yet, <HI>bear</HI> his Sight:</L>
<L>That, from his own dire Mouth, we may compell</L>
<L>Di&s;covery, of his Guilt's commi&s;&s;ion'd <HI>Cau&s;e:</HI></L>
<L>And, to the Bottom, &s;earch this horrid Tale.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Euricles.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Erox</HI>!&mdash;the Tyrant's Mini&s;ter of Death.</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="37" REF="36">
<HEAD>SCENE V.</HEAD>
<STAGE>MEROPE. ISMENE. EROX.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ero.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(a&s;ide)</HI></STAGE>
Now, aid me, wily Powers of winning Art!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>How now! What bold Intru&s;ion plac'd thee here?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ero.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Queen, of the Kingdom's Lord! his Heart's high Empre&s;s!</L>
<L>Suffer a Voice unequal to the Ta&s;k,</L>
<L>To wrong th' intru&s;ted Sen&s;e of <HI>his</HI> told Grief</L>
<L>Who &s;ends me to <HI>condole</HI> you.&mdash;<HI>Poliphontes</HI>,</L>
<L>Had you but &s;mooth'd that Brow's Maje&s;tic Bend,</L>
<L>I meant to have &s;aid, the <HI>King</HI>,&mdash;this Moment, heard</L>
<L>The Fate, mo&s;t pitied, of the Prince, your <HI>Son</HI></L>
<L>Heard, and takes equal Part, in all your Wrongs.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>More</HI>, than his Part, he takes, in what is Mine.</L>
<L>El&s;e had he never dar'd a&s;pire, to &s;eize</L>
<L>His Ma&s;ter's Throne; nor <HI>Name</HI> my murther'd Son.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ero.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Wi&s;hing, he waits but <HI>Leave</HI>. Re&s;pect is <HI>delicate</HI>,</L>
<L>And wou'd not, un-admitted, <HI>now</HI>, approach.</L>
<L>Fain wou'd he talk of Comfort, to <HI>your</HI> Sorrows,</L>
<L>Who, weeping, wants the Power to curb his <HI>own</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What wou'd your artful Sender come, to <HI>&s;ay?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ero.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>To beg, that to <HI>his</HI> Hand you wou'd commit.</L>
<L>This hateful Murd'rer's <HI>Puni&s;hment</HI>.&mdash;He glows</L>
<L>For Vengeance on &s;uch Guilt. Should think his Claim</L>
<L>Unworthy a Crown's Tru&s;t; le&s;s worthy <HI>yours</HI>,</L>
<L>Cou'd he forget, that <HI>Ju&s;tice</HI> props a Throne.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>No. Tell him <HI>no</HI>. My Hand revenges, <HI>here</HI>.</L>
<L>Too &s;hort of Reach, Heav'n knows! but what it <HI>can</HI>.</L>
<L><PB N="38" REF="37">It <HI>&s;hall:</HI> and neither a&s;ks, nor bears, <HI>his</HI> Aid.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ero.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>The King too tenderly regards your Will,</L>
<L>To cro&s;s it, ev'n in <HI>Anger</HI>.&mdash;le&s;s, in <HI>Rea&s;on</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;I humbly take my Leave.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I grant it, gladly.</L>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Erox.</STAGE>
<L>Hunted on every Side, why waits Di&s;tre&s;s,</L>
<L>Till &s;till <HI>new</HI> Growths of Angui&s;h, <HI>more</HI>, oppre&s;s?</L>
<L>How poor a Thing is <HI>Life</HI>, drag'd on to Age,</L>
<L>To &s;tand, the pitied Mark, of Fortune's Rage!</L>
<L><HI>Death</HI> &s;huts out Mis'ry: and can, be&s;t, re&s;train</L>
<L>The Rack of In&s;ult, and the <HI>Wring</HI> of Pain</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER><HI>The End of the</HI> SECOND ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<PB N="39" REF="38">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The Tomb of</HI> CRESPHONTES.</STAGE>
<STAGE>NARBAS <HI>alone</HI>.</STAGE>
<L>HAIL, venerable <HI>Gho&s;t!</HI> hail, &s;acred <HI>Tomb!</HI></L>
<L>Hail, heartwept <HI>Manes</HI> of my <HI>murther'd Lord!</HI></L>
<L>My <HI>la&s;t</HI> &s;ad Object, in <HI>Mycene</HI>'s Domes,</L>
<L>Was <HI>Thy</HI> maje&s;tic Eyebeam quench'd in Blood!</L>
<L><HI>Now</HI>, late returning, my <HI>own</HI> dim old <HI>Sight</HI></L>
<L>Weeps into <HI>Blindne&s;s</HI>, o'er this <HI>King</HI>'s <HI>la&s;t Bed:</HI></L>
<L>Where &s;ilent Marble veils imperial Du&s;t,</L>
<L>And &s;pares, from All thy Power, but This poor <HI>Stone</HI>,</L>
<L>To <HI>bound</HI> Thy death-&s;hrunk Reign!&mdash;yet, <HI>here</HI>, even HERE!</L>
<L>Sigh'd but <HI>Eumenes</HI> o'er this &s;olemn Scene,</L>
<L><HI>Narbas</HI> had <HI>hop'd</HI> to <HI>&s;oothe</HI> Thy &s;orrowing <HI>Shade</HI>.</L>
<L>How &s;hall I meet his <HI>Mother</HI>'s mournful Eye,</L>
<L>Who bring <HI>new</HI> Weight, to Woes <HI>o'ercharg'd before</HI>.</L>
<L>From every madd'ning Street, I hear loud Shouts,</L>
<L>Tho&s;e execrable Bawds, to flatter'd Power!</L>
<L>Proclaim the Traitor <HI>Poliphontes</HI>, King.</L>
<L>He! who, from Clime to Clime, track'd our &s;ad Way!</L>
<L>Held, like a hunted Deer, his Prince, in Chace;</L>
<L>Hot in Pur&s;uit, for <HI>Murder!</HI>&mdash;Each known Pro&s;pect,</L>
<L>Each Point, each Outlet of this neighb'ring Palace,</L>
<L>Brings to afflicted Mem'ry &s;ome new Stroke</L>
<L>Of Sorrow, fre&s;h to Pain&mdash;tho' fifteen Winters</L>
<L>Have &s;now'd their whitene&s;s on me, &s;ince they fell!</L>
<L>Wou'd, I cou'd find the Face of &s;ome old Friend!</L>
<L>But, what Court Friend&s;hip's Life <HI>la&s;ts</HI>, fifteen Winters:</L>
<L><PB N="40" REF="39">&mdash;Soft. Whom has Heaven &s;ent, here? If Inno|cence&mdash;</L>
<L>Dwells yet on Earth, &s;uch Looks as the&s;e mu&s;t <HI>hou&s;e</HI> it.</L>
<STAGE><HI>Starts, as</HI> I&s;men&eacute; <HI>comes nearer</HI>.</STAGE>
<L>Ble&s;s the re&s;embled <HI>Mother</HI>'s copied Softne&s;s!</L>
<L>'Tis my <HI>I&s;men&eacute;:</HI> 'Tis my own dear <HI>Daughter</HI>.</L>
<L>Time cannot hide her, from a Parent's Eye:</L>
<L>Child as &s;he was&mdash; and chang'd &s;ince la&s;t I &s;aw her.</L>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>NARBAS, ISMEN&Eacute;, <HI>follow'd by a Train of Virgins in white, who bring Ba&s;kets, and &s;trew Flowers on the Tomb</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ISMENE.</SPEAKER>
<L>Who is this bold Unknown? So &s;agely form'd!</L>
<L>Yet indi&s;creetly rude&mdash;at &s;uch an Hour,</L>
<L>To break, abruptly, on the Queen's &s;ad Purpo&s;e!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Faire&s;t, of Forms &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Who <HI>are</HI> you?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Chide me not,</L>
<L>Sweet Picture of the Powers, who &s;hed &s;oft Pity!</L>
<L>&mdash;I am a very friendle&s;s, weak, old Man.</L>
<L>Once, I was Servant, to the Queen <HI>you</HI> &s;erve;</L>
<L>O, grant the gracious Privilege, to <HI>&s;ee</HI> her.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Rev'rend, and Wi&s;e! The fir&s;t, I &s;ee you <HI>are:</HI></L>
<L>The la&s;t, my Heart conceives you&mdash;what a Time</L>
<L>Have your mi&s;guided Wants unaptly cho&s;en!</L>
<L>Your Sight wou'd, now, offend her.&mdash; Deep Di|&s;tre&s;s,</L>
<L>From dire Solemnity of Purpo&s;e, brings her,</L>
<L>&mdash;Twere prudent to withdraw.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(in a low Voice.)</HI></STAGE>
Come near&mdash;<HI>I&s;men&eacute;</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Immortal Powers! Who can it be?&mdash;He knows me!</L>
<L>Fain wou'd I mix wild <HI>Hope</HI>, with Fear and Wonder.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>approaching him.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="41" REF="40">
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Thou art my <HI>Child</HI>. Kind Heaven has &s;ent thee, to me.</L>
<L>&mdash; Be cautious&mdash;and ob&s;erve.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(Kneeling)</HI></STAGE>
Prophetic Heart!</L>
<L>Oh, Sir&mdash;I <HI>cannot</HI> &s;peak!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(Rai&s;ing her)</HI></STAGE>
Hide thy Surprize,</L>
<L>Ere yet &s;ome dang'rous <HI>Note</HI> detects our Meeting.</L>
<L>&mdash;Soft as thy Eyes <HI>I&s;men&eacute;</HI>, be thy <HI>Voice</HI>.</L>
<L>And an&s;wer, to my Que&s;tion&mdash;where is the Queen?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>She lives, this moment: but the next, &s;he <HI>dies</HI>.</L>
<L>Sorrowing &s;he comes,&mdash;to offer on this Tomb,</L>
<L>Her Life's <HI>la&s;t</HI> Sacrifice&mdash;a dreadful Victim!</L>
<L>&mdash;The <HI>Murd'rer</HI> of her <HI>Son</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Eumenes</HI> dead?&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Alas, Sir! cou'd you be a Stranger to it?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Bla&s;t! to my Soul's be&s;t Hope.&mdash;Who <HI>dar'd</HI> this Villainy?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>A Youth, who found him in <HI>Alcides' Temple</HI>.</L>
<L>One, from who&s;e Air of manly Mode&s;ty</L>
<L>None, &s;urely cou'd have fear'd&mdash;behold! he <HI>comes</HI>,</L>
<L>That fetter'd Criminal is He.&mdash;Oh, Sir!</L>
<L>Where will you, now, be hid?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>In Death, <HI>I&s;men&eacute;:</HI></L>
<L>If I now hear and &s;ee &mdash;and am not <HI>dreaming!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>From the Queen's Eye, I dare no longer.&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(holding her)</HI></STAGE>
Stay.</L>
<L>Queens, Kings, nor Gods, &s;hall tear thee from my Arm,</L>
<L>Till thou ha&s;t heard me fully</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Speak&mdash;Command.</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="42" REF="41">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Solemn Proce&s;&s;ion to a</HI> Dead <HI>March</HI>. Merop&eacute;. Eu|ricles, <HI>with the Sword</HI>. Eumenes, in <HI>Chains, Guards. Prie&s;ts, as to Sacrifice&mdash;The Queen goes up weeping, and kneels &s;ilent, at the Tomb. While the Re&s;t range them&s;elves, on each Side the Scene.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>NARBAS, <HI>to</HI> ISMEN&Eacute;.</STAGE>
<L>Some black-&s;oul'd <HI>Fiend</HI>, &s;ome Fury ris'n from Hell,</L>
<L>Has darken'd all Di&s;cernment!&mdash;Call'd&s;t thou not</L>
<L>That fetter'd Youth the <HI>Murd'rer</HI> of <HI>Eumenes?</HI></L>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I call'd him &s;o, too truly.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>He is <HI>Eumenes</HI>.</L>
<L>What angry God mi&s;leads the Queen to Madne&s;s?</L>
<L>She dreams <HI>Eumenes kill'd</HI>&mdash;and <HI>kills Eumenes!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Now are my Heart's late Tremblings well explain'd.</L>
<L>Quick let me ru&s;h, and <HI>warn</HI> her erring Hand.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Not for a thou&s;and Worlds&mdash;to &s;ave him, <HI>So</HI>,</L>
<L>Were but to lo&s;e him, <HI>Surer&mdash;Poliphontes</HI></L>
<L>Has Ears and Eyes too near us.&mdash;<HI>Pray</HI>; and be dumb.</L>
<STAGE><HI>Sad and &s;olemn Mu&s;ick. Then a SONG, of Sacrifice: by Mr.</HI> Beard, <HI>as Chief Prie&s;t</HI>.</STAGE>
<LG N="1">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<L><HI>Hear</HI>, from the dark and &s;ilent Shade!</L>
<L><HI>Hear</HI>, ye pale Bands of <HI>Death!</HI></L>
<L>Gliding from <HI>Graves</HI>, where once your <HI>Bones</HI> were laid,</L>
<L><HI>Receive</HI> a Murd'rer's Breath.</L>
<L><HI>Chorus, of Prie&s;ts and Virgins.</HI></L>
<L>Receive a Murd'rer's Breath.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2">
<PB N="43" REF="42">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L>Doom'd to <HI>atone</HI> the Blood he drew,</L>
<L>Fates! lend your <HI>E$on Bowl</HI>.</L>
<L><HI>Take</HI> the devoted Stream, to Vengeance due,</L>
<L>And <HI>catch</HI> the parting Soul.</L>
<L><HI>Chorus, of Prie&s;ts and Virgins.</HI></L>
<L>And <HI>catch</HI> the parting Soul.</L>
<STAGE>Merop&eacute;, <HI>ri&s;ing and coming forward</HI>.</STAGE>
<L>Where is this Victim&mdash;odious, to All Powers,</L>
<L>But <HI>one</HI>,&mdash;the dreadful <HI>Neme&s;is?</HI></L>
</LG>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>The Guards bring up</HI> Eumenes.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Yet, er'e he dies,</L>
<L>'Twere fit, &s;ome Force of Torture &s;hould compell him</L>
<L>To name his vile Accomplices.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>It <HI>&s;hall</HI>.</L>
<L>Say, Mon&s;ter! what provok'd thee to this Guilt:</L>
<L>And what A&s;&s;ociates join'd thee.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I appeal</L>
<L>The Gods, who find it fit my Soul &s;hou'd buy,</L>
<L>At this dear Rate, the Moment's Hope you lent it;</L>
<L>Tho&s;e <HI>Gods</HI> can <HI>witne&s;s</HI> for me; They! who cur&s;e</L>
<L>The perjur'd, and di&s;claim the Ba&s;e one's Safety.</L>
<L>My Lips dete&s;t Impo&s;ture: bold, and clear</L>
<L>As Day's un&s;ullied Light, they trace Truth, <HI>plainly</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;Nor know I, by what Change, in Heaven's high Will,</L>
<L>I, who of late &s;o ble&s;s'd, had touch'd your <HI>Pity</HI>,</L>
<L>Fall, now, beneath your <HI>Anger</HI>!</L>
</SP>
<STAGE>Merop&eacute;, <HI>taking the Sword, from</HI> Euricles.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>View this Sword.</L>
<L><HI>Know</HI> you the dreadful Object.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Twas the Villain's,</L>
<L>My ju&s;t Hand puni&s;h'd with it.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Seize him. Rend him.</L>
<L>Swift to the trembling Altar, drag the Traitor.</L>
<L>He <HI>owns</HI> it! glories, in his bloody Crime:</L>
<L>And my &s;hock'd Soul <HI>akes</HI>, at him.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>The Guards &s;eize him.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="44" REF="43">
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(&s;truggling.)</HI></STAGE>
Off&mdash;away &mdash;</L>
<L>Stay your re&s;i&s;ted Rage.&mdash;I <HI>will</HI> be heard;</L>
<L>One la&s;t loud Word&mdash;in Spite of Arms and In&s;ult.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(after a Signal to the Guards, who quit</HI> Eumenes.)</STAGE>
Thou then, who deal'&s;t in Death, can'&s;t find Death fearful.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>No, Madam! you mi&s;take. Death &s;hakes the <HI>happy:</HI></L>
<L>But He who is a Wretch receives him gladly.</L>
<L>&mdash;Yet, 'gain&s;t imputed Guilt, the humble&s;t, wrong'd</L>
<L>Ri&s;e, in bold Innocence, re&s;ign'd, no longer.</L>
<L>&mdash;Low as I am, and you &s;o rais'd in Power,</L>
<L>Were not your <HI>Griefs</HI> more awful than your <HI>Anger</HI>,</L>
<L>I had reproach'd your Rage, and blam'd your Blindne&s;s.</L>
<L>&mdash;Tell me, nor let your Pride deface your Pity,</L>
<L>Who&s;e, &s;o high-rated Blood was This I &s;hed?</L>
<L>And what new Int're&s;t finds he, in your Favour?</L>
<L>&mdash;If he was dear to <HI>You</HI>, curs'd be my Memory,</L>
<L>Or I had rather lo&s;t my <HI>Own</HI>, than <HI>His</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Where has this cruel Wretch been taught Deceit?</L>
<L>Why was that Look, &s;o like <HI>Cre&s;phontes</HI>, His!</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Half Fainting.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Great Queen! &s;u&s;tain your Purpo&s;e. Think of <HI>Vengeance</HI>.</L>
<L>The Laws of Nature,&mdash;and the Lives of Kings.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Do Laws and Kings, then, call Inju&s;tice <HI>Vengeance</HI>.</L>
<L>Shame on the Great! why long'd my Eyes for <HI>Courts?</HI></L>
<L>Courts, where the Pride of Guilt lays Claim to Honour.</L>
<L>&mdash;Haughty of Heart, why have they Souls thus abject?</L>
<L>You threaten, prai&s;e, fright, flatter, and in&s;ult me!</L>
<L>&mdash;Gods! what a creeping climbing, hot cold, Creature,</L>
<L>Is this big little Flutt'rer, call'd a <HI>Courtier!</HI></L>
<L>&mdash;Yet, oh! 'twas <HI>ju&s;t</HI>.&mdash;I left my Father, ra&s;hly;</L>
<L>Felt not HIS Pangs: weigh'd not the Tears I co&s;t him.</L>
<L><PB N="45" REF="44">Fate drew me from my Fore&s;t's crimele&s;s Quiet,</L>
<L>Into the World's loud In&s;ignificance;</L>
<L>Deaf to the Warnings of a Father's Wi&s;dom:</L>
<L>And a griev'd Mother's Bodings.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Mother</HI>, &s;aid he!</L>
<L>Barbarian! ha'&s;t thou yet a <HI>Mother</HI>, left thee?</L>
<L>I <HI>was</HI> a Mother, too.&mdash;till Thy <HI>fell</HI> Hand</L>
<L>Depriv'd me of a <HI>Son</HI>&mdash;and all Life's Comforts.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>A Son!&mdash;<HI>your</HI> Son?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Mine, Mon&s;ter! Murd'rer! Mine.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>If <HI>Such</HI> was my Misfortune, Such my <HI>Cur&s;e</HI>,</L>
<L>If Heaven has made it <HI>po&s;&s;ible</HI>&mdash;that He,</L>
<L>Who, in a fatal Moment, err'd&mdash;and fell</L>
<L>By my ill-de&s;tin'd Ra&s;hne&s;s, was <HI>Your</HI> Son,</L>
<L>Earth holds not &s;uch another Wretch as I am!</L>
<L>And Mercy's fainte&s;t Glimp&s;e &s;hou'd &s;hun to reach me.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Perfidious, execrable Slave!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Yet, <HI>hear</HI> me.</L>
<STAGE>Eumenes, <HI>here, offers to &s;peak, and</HI> Merop&eacute; <HI>interrupts him</HI>.</STAGE>
<L>&mdash;Stop his dete&s;ted Mouth.&mdash;If thou dar'&s;t <HI>pray</HI>.</L>
<L>Rai&s;e thy dumb <HI>Hands:</HI> and a&s;k, in vain, from Heaven,</L>
<L>The Mercy, thou denied'&s;t my dying Son.</L>
<L>Force the doom'd Victim to the Alter's Foot,</L>
<L><HI>Veil</HI> him from <HI>Light</HI>, no more to be beheld:</L>
<L><HI>Hide</HI> his quench'd <HI>Eyes</HI>, for ever.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Two Prie&s;ts approaching, with a Veil, he &s;natches it, and throws it from him.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Off!</HI> ye vain <HI>Forms!</HI></L>
<L>Cover the Eyes of <HI>Cowards:</HI> Mine di&s;dain ye.</L>
<L>Mine can, with &s;tedfa&s;t and <HI>advancing Scorn</HI>,</L>
<L>Look in Death's <HI>Face</HI>, full-&s;ighted&mdash;When It comes</L>
<L>Tis to be <HI>met</HI>, not <HI>hid</HI>.&mdash;On.&mdash;I <HI>provoke</HI> it.</L>
<L>Welcome, Eternal Day!&mdash; <HI>Bad World</HI>, farewel.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Advances, between the Prie&s;ts, to the Tomb&mdash; follow'd by the Queen</HI>, Euricles, I&s;men&eacute;, <HI>&amp;c.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(at the Tomb&mdash;with the Sword drawn, and</HI> Eumenes <HI>kneeling ready.)</HI></STAGE>
Shade, of my Murder'd</L>
<L><HI>Hu&s;band!&mdash; hear</HI> my Call.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="46" REF="45"><HI>Chorus, of Singers Voices. Oh! hear.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Soul, of my bleeding <HI>Son!</HI> hear, <HI>thou</HI>&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Chorus, of Singers Voices. Oh! hear.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Un-expiated Souls!&mdash;if, in tho&s;e Glooms,</L>
<L>Where walk the &s;ullen Gho&s;ts of earth-wrong'd Kings,</L>
<L>You hear Atonement's Voice, and wait Redre&s;s,</L>
<L><HI>Ri&s;e</HI>, from your dark Domains!</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Chorus, of Singers Voices. Oh! ri&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>&mdash;<HI>Thou</HI>, la&s;t,</L>
<L>Tremend'ous Power! pale Godde&s;s! pre&s;ent, &s;till,</L>
<L>To direful <HI>Vengeance!</HI> nerve this lifted Arm,</L>
<L>And <HI>thus</HI> a&s;&s;i&s;ting &mdash;</L>
<STAGE>I&s;men&eacute; <HI>preventing the Blow</HI>, Narbas <HI>breaks into Sight, and cries out loudly</HI>,</STAGE>
<L><HI>Stay, Stay</HI>, that bloody Purpo&s;e.</L>
<L>Death has already been too bu&s;y, here:</L>
<L>And Heaven di&s;claims &s;uch Sacrifice.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(in a frighted and trembling Attitude.)</HI></STAGE>
Who <HI>art</HI> thou?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(&mdash;a&s;ide&mdash;to the Queen.)</HI></STAGE>
Your Victim is your</L>
<L><HI>Son</HI>,&mdash;the Prince, <HI>Eumenes</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE>Merop&eacute; <HI>lets fall the Sword&mdash;a&s;toni&s;h'd, and trembling</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(rai&s;ing him&s;elf to look round.)</HI></STAGE>
I heard a well-known Voice, now heard no longer.</L>
<L>Emerge, &s;ad Eyes! once more, from the Graves Brink,</L>
<L>To view what <HI>&s;eem'd</HI> &mdash; oh! 'tis&mdash;It is&mdash;My <HI>Father!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(a&s;ide, to Eumenes.)</HI></STAGE>
Hear: and be dumb.</L>
<L>Thy Fate, unwary Youth!</L>
<L>Depends upon thy <HI>Silence</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Whence, ye dark Powers!</L>
<L>Can all the&s;e My&s;t'ries ri&s;e!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh!&mdash;'tis too much&mdash;</L>
<L>And Life and I are <HI>lo&s;t</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Faints: and is &s;upported by</HI> I&s;men&eacute;.</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="47" REF="46">
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Stay your unhallow'd <HI>Rites:</HI> the Queen's in Danger.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Lend us your loyal Help, ye <HI>Virgin</HI> Train.</L>
<STAGE><HI>The Virgins advance.</HI></STAGE>
<L>Quit, rev'rend <HI>Prie&s;ts!</HI> quit your too bloody Sacrifice.</L>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt Prie&s;ts.</HI></STAGE>
<L>And you, ye watchful <HI>Guards!</HI> draw near, and follow.</L>
<L>While I &s;ecure the <HI>Victim</HI> for his Fate.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(to Eumenes.)</HI></STAGE>
Shun me: and patient wait th' important <HI>Cau&s;e</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>O, bid me, e'er I die, but hope your Pardon:</L>
<L>And, if I leave <HI>you</HI> ble&s;s'd&mdash;'tis all my Prayer.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>No more.&mdash;The Gods, who love, <HI>reward</HI> thy Virtue!</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>The Soldiers, and</HI> Euricles, <HI>go off, with</HI> Eumenes.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Kind Heaven re&s;tores the Queen.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Off.&mdash;Give her Air.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Where!&mdash;whither have ye brought me?</L>
<L>&mdash;Where is <HI>Euricles?</HI></L>
<L>&mdash;<HI>I&s;men&eacute;?</HI>&mdash;what means This!&mdash;Why weep my Virgins?</L>
<L>&mdash;Oh! I have <HI>kill'd</HI> him:
<STAGE><HI>(looking wildly round her)</HI></STAGE>
for I &s;ee him <HI>not:</HI></L>
<L>And I am doom'd to Pains, in Life immortal.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Ea&s;e your &s;ad Heart's too apprehen&s;ive Startings.</L>
<L><HI>Euricles</HI> holds him &s;afe: And nothing's known.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Still this kind Vi&s;ion haunts me.&mdash;Art thou <HI>Narbas?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Let my <HI>Tears</HI> an&s;wer&mdash;in this Gu&s;h of Joy&mdash;</L>
<L>I give you back my Ma&s;ter&mdash;your <HI>Eumenes</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(on her Knees.)</HI></STAGE>
Oh, gracious Heaven! &s;upport a Woman's Weakne&s;s:</L>
<L>And, what my <HI>Heart</HI>, yet panting, fails to <HI>utter</HI>,</L>
<L>Take, from my Soul's touch'd Sen&s;e; and <HI>make</HI> my Prayer.</L>
<L><PB N="48" REF="47">You are too <HI>Great</HI>, for Thanks! too <HI>Good</HI>, for Duty!</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Ri&s;es.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(re-entering ha&s;tily.)</HI></STAGE>
Death! to th' in&s;atiate</L>
<L>Tyrant's Thir&s;t of In&s;ult!</L>
<L>&mdash;This Royal Scandal, to the Name he &s;teals,</L>
<L>Has, with &s;ome fatal Purpo&s;e, <HI>&s;eiz'd</HI> the King;</L>
<L>And holds him, to examine.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(going.)</HI></STAGE>
Follow me.</L>
<L>Now &s;hall he &s;ee, what <HI>Marks</HI> denote the <HI>Queen</HI>;</L>
<L>What <HI>Diff'rence</HI>, 'twixt the Guilty, and the Wrong'd.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Madam! &mdash;It mu&s;t not be.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Stay: Curb this Ra&s;hne&s;s.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Is he not mine! Is he not <HI>yours?</HI>&mdash;your <HI>King?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>The Moment you confe&s;s That dang'rous Truth,</L>
<L>No God, but hated <HI>Hymen</HI>, &s;aves <HI>Eumenes</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>There, thou ha&s;t let in Light, upon my Soul,</L>
<L>That crowds it with black Shapes, and frights Di&s;dain!</L>
<L>&mdash;Rather than <HI>wed</HI> this <HI>Poliphontes</HI>.&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Wed</HI> him?</L>
<L>WED&mdash;<HI>Poliphontes!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Him.</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>The World's la&s;t Groan,</L>
<L>Wrapt in &s;urrounding Fires, had <HI>le&s;s</HI> amaz'd me!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Tis with That View the People call him <HI>King</HI>.</L>
<L>Since he reveng'd <HI>Cre&s;phontes' Blood</HI>, they &s;ay,</L>
<L><HI>He</HI>, be&s;t&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>He!</HI>&mdash;Every Cur&s;e of Death &s;urround him!</L>
<L>He! He reveng'd!&mdash;The Villain's own damn'd Train</L>
<L><HI>Shed,&mdash;&s;pilt</HI> it. I beheld 'em: Trac'd the <HI>Fiend</HI></L>
<L>Thro' all his dark Di&s;gui&s;es&mdash;thro' Night's Eye</L>
<L>Saw the pale Murd'rer Stalk, amid&s;t his Furies.</L>
<L><HI>His</HI> was the half-hid Torch,&mdash;the Po&s;tern Key,</L>
<L>That open'd to the Rebel's Rage the Palace.</L>
<L>&mdash; In the pierc'd infant Brea&s;ts of <HI>two</HI> doom'd Innocents,</L>
<L><PB N="49" REF="48">I <HI>&s;aw</HI> him plunge his Poignard: Twice receiv'd it,</L>
<L>Deep, in my <HI>own</HI>, encumber'd with my Charge:</L>
<L>Struggling, to bear the third <HI>&s;av'd</HI> Prince to &s;helter;</L>
<L>And, track'd by my own Blood, with Pain e&s;cap'd him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>When will my growing Horrors reach their <HI>End!</HI></L>
<L>Oh! my fix'd Hate was <HI>In&s;tinct</HI>. Something, fatal,</L>
<L>Dwelt on this dreadful Brow, and bad me <HI>&s;hun</HI> him.</L>
<L>Blind! headlong! ill-di&s;cerning! noi&s;e-driv'n People!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(looking out.)</HI></STAGE>
Darkne&s;s and Death involve me, but he <HI>comes!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Can the Gods leave That <HI>po&s;&s;ible?</HI>&mdash;the Mon&s;ter!</L>
<L>But, He who puts on Guilt, mu&s;t ca&s;t off Shame.</L>
<L>&mdash;<HI>Narbas</HI>, be <HI>hid</HI>, this Moment&mdash;
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Narbas.</STAGE></L>
<STAGE>&mdash;<HI>Euricles!</HI></STAGE>
<L>Fly thou&mdash;find Acce&s;s to my mournful Son:</L>
<L>See him &s;et free&mdash;but keep the Secret from him.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Euricles.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE IV.</HEAD>
<STAGE>MEROP&Eacute;, ISMEN&Eacute;, POLIPHONTES <HI>in Nuptial Robes</HI>, EROX, <HI>and Train</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Health, to my <HI>Sovereign, late!</HI>! Now &mdash; &s;o the States</L>
<L>Decree&mdash;my <HI>Wife!</HI>&mdash;my Si&s;ter! and my Soul!</L>
<L>Dre&s;s'd is the <HI>Altar</HI>; and the Prie&s;ts attend.</L>
<L>&mdash;Nay, do not turn a&s;ide, and &s;hun your Triumph.</L>
<L>Look &mdash; and admire the Wonders of your Power!</L>
<L>The God of Love, to-day, &s;moothes all my Wrinkles:</L>
<L>And I am taught by Joy to &s;mile back <HI>Youth</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;One Care alone precedes impatient Love.</L>
<L>They tell me, your too tender Heart <HI>recoil'd:</HI></L>
<L>And <HI>lo&s;t</HI> your purpos'd Vengeance.&mdash;Let it <HI>be</HI>.</L>
<L>Beauty was meant to <HI>wound</HI>, a gentler Way.</L>
<L><HI>Mine</HI>, be the Stroke of Ju&s;tice.&mdash;When I view</L>
<L><PB N="50" REF="49">This murd'rous Stripling, thro' the Grief he brought you,</L>
<L>Pity di&s;dains his Cau&s;e; and Fate <HI>demands</HI> him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I find my&s;elf, 'tis true, too weak, for Vengeance.</L>
<L>Wou'd I had Power, more equal to my Wrongs!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Leave it to <HI>Me:</HI> 'Tis a King's Right.&mdash;</L>
<L>I <HI>claim</HI> it.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I &s;hall <HI>con&s;ider</HI> of it.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Why; what doubt you?</L>
<L><HI>Slackens</HI> your Anger? that your Vengeance he&s;itates!</L>
<L>Is your Son's Mem'ry now, le&s;s dear, than lately?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Peri&s;h, the <HI>Will</HI>, that wrongs him! but, this Murd'rer,</L>
<L>This <HI>Youth</HI>&mdash;they tell me you &s;u&s;pect Accomplices&mdash;</L>
<L>Were it not prudent to &s;u&s;pend his Fate,</L>
<L>'Till he declares, who join'd him?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What expect you</L>
<L>To clear, beyond your Son's known Fall?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>His <HI>Father's</HI>&mdash;</L>
<L>That was a Cup of <HI>Gall</HI>.&mdash;Oh! con&s;cious Guilt!</L>
<L>How dumb, thy Voice, unlook'd-for, &s;trikes the Bold!
<STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(after a Pau&s;e.)</HI></STAGE>
Well&mdash;ev'n of That to$,</L>
<L>We our&s;elf will a&s;k him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>You are too bu&s;y, Sir! in a Pur&s;uit,</L>
<L>That, lea&s;t, admits <HI>your</HI> Quick'ning.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Strange Perplexity!</L>
<L>That what mo&s;t &s;eeks your Ea&s;e &s;hou'd mo&s;t <HI>offend!</HI></L>
<L>But, &s;pring it, whence it may, the <HI>Cau&s;e</HI> remov'd,</L>
<L>There, ends the Doubt, and Pain.&mdash;This Wretch &s;hall <HI>die</HI>.
<STAGE><HI>Going.</HI></STAGE></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Barbarian! horrible, inhuman&mdash;<HI>Sir!</HI></L>
<L>Why have you &s;ought to &s;tartle me?&mdash;I feared&mdash;</L>
<L>You meant to &s;natch my Victim from&mdash;my Vengeance.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>But&mdash;&s;hall he <HI>really</HI> die?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Die!&mdash;<HI>Who?</HI> &mdash;He&mdash;die?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>The Murd'rer of your Son.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I go, this Moment;</L>
<L>And will, alone, examine him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="51" REF="50">
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Stay, Madam.</L>
<L>This new Embarra&s;&s;ment, of mingled Pains;</L>
<L>This Tenderne&s;s in Rage; the&s;e Hopes, Fears, Startings,</L>
<L>This Art, to colour &s;ome ill-hid Di&s;tre&s;s,</L>
<L>That ca&s;ts <HI>Confu&s;ion</HI> o'er your troubled Soul:</L>
<L>Half Sentences, broke &s;hort; Looks, fill'd with Horror,</L>
<L>Are Nature's thin <HI>Di&s;gui&s;e</HI>, to cover Danger.</L>
<L>&mdash;Something you will not <HI>tell</HI> alarms my Caution;</L>
<L>And bids my &s;ummon'd <HI>Fear</HI> take Place of Love.</L>
<L>&mdash; In ent'ring, here, I had a Glimp&s;e, but now,</L>
<L>Of an old Man, who &s;eem'd to &s;hun my Pre&s;ence.</L>
<L>Why is he fled?&mdash;Who was he?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Scarce yet call'd</L>
<L>A <HI>King</HI>&mdash;and &s;ee! already fill'd with Jealou&s;ies!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Be kind, and bear your Part, then.&mdash;</L>
<L>Burthens, &s;har'd,</L>
<L>Pre&s;s light the eas'd Su&s;tainers.&mdash;Come; your Hand.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>A Moment &s;ince, you talk'd but of Revenge:</L>
<L>Now, 'tis again all Love&mdash;Away: Keep &s;eparate,</L>
<L>Two Pa&s;&s;ions, Nature, never, yet, &s;aw join'd.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Let it be &s;o, then. Death &s;hall &s;trait remove</L>
<L>That Ob&s;tacle: And but one Wi&s;h remains.</L>
<L>Follow, at Lei&s;ure, <HI>you:</HI> While I prepare.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Poliphontes.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Act for me, now, and &s;ave me, Great <HI>Alcides!</HI></L>
<L>To Power like thine, all Things are po&s;&s;ible:</L>
<L>And Grief, oppre&s;s'd on Earth, finds Friends in Heaven.</L>
<L>Then when the woe-pre&s;s'd Heart is tir'd with Care,</L>
<L>And every <HI>human</HI> Pro&s;pect bids <HI>de&s;pair</HI>,</L>
<L>Break but one Gleam of <HI>heav'nly</HI> Comfort, in;</L>
<L>And a new Race of <HI>Triumphs</HI>, thence, begin.</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER><HI>The End of the</HI> THIRD ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="act">
<PB N="52" REF="51">
<HEAD>ACT. IV.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE. I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>The Ca&s;tle of <HI>Poliphontes</HI>.</STAGE>
<STAGE>POLIPHONTES. EROX.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>POLIPHONTES.</SPEAKER>
<L>SHE has <HI>her</HI> Views, I mine.&mdash;I &s;hould have fear'd,</L>
<L>Some Hint's officious Note had reach'd her Ear;</L>
<L>I &s;hou'd have dreamt, her Eyes had catch'd &s;ome Glance,</L>
<L>Some glimm'ring Entrance for admitted Light,</L>
<L>To guide <HI>Di&s;covery</HI> down the dark Aby&s;s,</L>
<L>Where my clo&s;e Crimes lies <HI>veil'd</HI>, in dumb Ob|&s;curity.</L>
<L>&mdash;But, that I know &s;he is a WOMAN&mdash;<HI>Erox!</HI></L>
<L>And <HI>born</HI> to be capricious.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ero.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Pride&mdash;not Di&s;ta&s;te,</L>
<L>Holds out her Heart, again&s;t you.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Let her keep it.</L>
<L>My Hope is humbler, <HI>Erox</HI>. 'Tis her Hand</L>
<L>I &s;eek: <HI>Hearts</HI> are Girls' Gifts to School-boy Lovers.</L>
<L>Now, let her Spleen &s;tart wild. When Times &s;erve aptly,</L>
<L>Means &s;hall be found to curb it. Thou art come</L>
<L>From founding this fierce captive Son of Wonder.</L>
<L>What have thy Thoughts concluded?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ero.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Tis not <HI>He</HI>.</L>
<L>No Race of <HI>Hercules</HI> need, there, alarm you.</L>
<L>This but &s;ome wood-born Brave, of artle&s;s Ho|ne&s;ty;</L>
<L>Void of Ambition's Flame: Bold, blunt, and hone&s;t:</L>
<L>Fearle&s;s of Menace, ta&s;tele&s;s of Reward,</L>
<L><PB N="53" REF="52">And &s;imply wanting <HI>Will</HI>, to dare, for Power.</L>
<L>He cannot be <HI>Eumenes</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Who, then, is he?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ero.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>He &s;ays he is a <HI>Shepherd</HI>'s Son &mdash; what, more,</L>
<L>He will not be provok'd, nor brib'd, to tell.</L>
<L>Firm without Fiercene&s;s; without Weakne&s;s gentle;</L>
<L>Open as Day-light: yet, as dumb, as Death!</L>
<L>Spite of my Prejudice, he forc'd my Prai&s;e;</L>
<L>And <HI>Hatred</HI> mu&s;t admire him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Prai&s;e him on.</L>
<L>Be what, or whom, he may, 'tis fit he <HI>die</HI>.</L>
<L>My Foes, too num'rous, taught me Skill too try'd,</L>
<L>To lean my Hope's light tru&s;t on harlot Fortune.</L>
<L>The <HI>People</HI>, who conclude his Puni&s;hment</L>
<L>Inflicted, for <HI>Eumenes'</HI> fan&s;ied Murder,</L>
<L>Will dream that Race <HI>extinct</HI>; and cleave to <HI>Me</HI>.</L>
<L>So Danger comes le&s;s near: Nor &s;hakes my Throne.</L>
<L>&mdash;What ha&s;t thou learnt, of that conceal'd Pre|&s;umer,</L>
<L>Who, when the Arm of <HI>Merop&eacute;</HI> was rais'd,</L>
<L>Re&s;train'd it, with &s;ome Power that touch'd her Soul.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ero.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>The young Man call'd him <HI>Father</HI>, Chance, it &s;eems,</L>
<L>In that nice Moment, brought him to his View.</L>
<L>He mov'd the Queen's Compa&s;&s;ion, for his Son,</L>
<L>Fled like a Wanton, from the Good Man's Care,</L>
<L>Who, in his Search, came &s;orrowing on, from <HI>Elis</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I cannot tru&s;t this Tale. Thou grow'&s;t too credulous,</L>
<L>My&s;terious Caution hangs too thick a <HI>Veil</HI></L>
<L>O'er all their late Proceedings. That old Man,</L>
<L>Left the Queen's Pre&s;ence, &s;tarting, at my Entrance.</L>
<L>Why was he hid, if a young Ru&s;tick's Father?</L>
<L>Why &s;hou'd <HI>my</HI> coming fright him? He has heard</L>
<L>Since then, his Son's redoubled Danger dwells</L>
<L>But in <HI>my</HI> Menace: Yet he comes not near me.</L>
<L>I had, ere now, beheld him at my Feet,</L>
<L>Had his Heart trembled with a Father's Terrors.</L>
<L><PB N="54" REF="53">&mdash;No matter who he is.&mdash;He moves my Fear?</L>
<L>And, ere my Eye-lids clo&s;e, he &s;leeps, in Death.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ero.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>See, Sir! he's <HI>free</HI>&mdash;and mark&mdash;the Queen, how <HI>near!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I note it, and determine.</L>
<L>&mdash;Now my Si&s;ter.</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>POLIPHONTES, EROX, MEROP&Eacute;, EURICLES, EU|MENES, <HI>and Guards</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>You &s;ee, Sir, I dare know, and <HI>u&s;e</HI>, my Rights.</L>
<L>How had your Will pre&s;um'd to hold my Victim?</L>
<L>Am I but Queen of Shadows? that my Vengeance</L>
<L>Mu&s;t move, as <HI>you</HI> direct it?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Nobly urg'd!</L>
<L>The Victim is your Right, requires <HI>your</HI> Hand:</L>
<L>Mine had defac'd your Ju&s;tice.&mdash;I a&s;&s;um'd</L>
<L>Pretence to aid it, but to fire your Langour.</L>
<L>Take Courage. I re&s;ign him. With his Blood</L>
<L>Wa&s;h this reluctant Faintne&s;s, from your Heart:</L>
<L>And give it Warmth to meet me at the Altar.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Horrid, and impious Hope!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Looks <HI>Love</HI> &s;o frightful?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE>(<HI>to</HI> Poliphontes.)</STAGE>
Who taught thee to a&s;|&s;ociate Love, with <HI>Cruelty?</HI></L>
<L>What Right has <HI>Cupid</HI> to a Captive's Blood?</L>
<L>&mdash;Yet, mi&s;pre&s;ume not, that I court thy Pity&mdash;</L>
<L>He has too poor a View from Life, to <HI>prize</HI> it,</L>
<L>Who&s;e Death can only &s;erve to &s;horten <HI>Pain</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;But, I am told, Thou call'&s;t thy&s;elf a <HI>King</HI>.</L>
<L><HI>Know</HI>, if thou <HI>art</HI> one, that the Poor have Rights:</L>
<L>And Power, in all it's Pride, is <HI>le&s;s</HI> than <HI>Ju&s;tice</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;I am a Stranger,&mdash;innocent,&mdash;and friendle&s;s,&mdash;</L>
<L>And That Protection, which thou <HI>w'&s;t</HI>, to All,</L>
<L>Is doubly due to me:&mdash;For, I'm unhappy.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Protection is for <HI>Worth:</HI>&mdash; Guilt call for Vengeance.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="55" REF="54">
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>And what does Wrong's licentious <HI>In&s;ult</HI> call for?</L>
<L>&mdash;In my own ju&s;t Defence, I <HI>kill'd</HI> a Robber:</L>
<L>Law call'd it <HI>Murder</HI>; and the Queen condemn'd me,</L>
<L>Queens may <HI>mi&s;take</HI>. Ev'n <HI>Gods</HI>, who LOVE, grow <HI>partial</HI>.</L>
<L>I pardon, ev'n th' Inju&s;tice, of a <HI>Mother:</HI></L>
<L>And cou'd have ble&s;s'd <HI>her</HI> Hand, beneath the Blow.</L>
<L><HI>Nature</HI> has Weakne&s;&s;es, that <HI>err</HI> to Virtue?</L>
<L>&mdash;But, What ha&s;t <HI>Thou</HI> to do with Mother's Ven|geance?</L>
<L>Law, that &s;hocks <HI>Equity</HI>, is <HI>Rea&s;on</HI>'s Murder.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>So young! &s;o wretched!&mdash;and &s;o <HI>arrogant!</HI></L>
<L>Methinks, the Pride of an <HI>Alcides'</HI> Blood</L>
<L>Cou'd &s;carce have &s;well'd a Soul to loftier <HI>Boldne&s;s!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Pity pre&s;umptuous Heat. 'Tis Youth's Prerogative,</L>
<L>To triumph in Imprudence. Bred, in Cotts,</L>
<L>Far from a Court's Politene&s;s, How &s;hould He</L>
<L>Have learnt Di&s;gui&s;e of Thought? or Power's Preten&s;ions?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Mean while, how happy &s;uch unpoli&s;h'd Plainne&s;s!</L>
<L>To move Defence, from Art &s;o &s;kill'd as <HI>Yours</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(a&s;ide.)</HI></STAGE>
Oh! my unguarded Terror!&mdash;</L>
<L>You are <HI>plea&s;ant</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>And you are wond'rous <HI>kind!</HI> Your Son, &s;ure! <HI>lives</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Lives! and <HI>&s;hall</HI> live. I tru&s;t him to the <HI>Gods:</HI></L>
<L>They <HI>can</HI>&mdash;they <HI>did</HI>, protect him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(a&s;ide.)</HI></STAGE>
Madam! Madam!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(a&s;ide.)</HI></STAGE>
Her fear-mix'd Anger will betray her Cau&s;e.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What cannot Woman's Pity! None who marks</L>
<L>The willing Pardon your &s;oft Looks in&s;ure him,</L>
<L>Can charge your Heart with Cruelty.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>My Looks,</L>
<L>Perhaps, hint Meanings, Prudence &s;hou'd decline</L>
<PB N="56" REF="55">
<GAP DESC="DUPLICATE">
<PB N="57" REF="56">
<GAP DESC="DUPLICATE">
<PB N="54" REF="57">
<GAP DESC="DUPLICATE">
<PB N="55" REF="58">
<GAP DESC="DUPLICATE">
<L><PB N="56" REF="59">To lend too loud a <HI>Tongue</HI> to.&mdash; but, there <HI>are</HI>,</L>
<L>Who&s;e <HI>Heart &s;peaks</HI> Nothing: Yet <HI>tells All</HI>, by Actions.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Mark, if I &s;peak not, <HI>now</HI>, my Heart's true Language.</L>
<L>&mdash;<HI>Traitor! receive thy Doom.</HI>
<STAGE><HI>Drawing his Sword.</HI></STAGE></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(interpo&s;ing)</HI></STAGE>
Strike <HI>here, here</HI>, Murd'rer!</L>
<L>Menace <HI>my</HI> Brea&s;t; not His.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Who&s;e Heart &s;peaks, <HI>now?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Now, ye Immortals! not to <HI>die</HI>, were, <HI>not</HI></L>
<L>To triumph. &mdash; To be pitied, <HI>here! thus</HI>, pitied!</L>
<L>By &s;uch a Queen as <HI>Merop&eacute;</HI> &mdash; 'tis Glory</L>
<L>That every Power beneath a <HI>God</HI> might envy!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>If you wou'd have him live, confe&s;s, <HI>Who is he?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>He &mdash; is &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE>(<HI>to</HI> I&s;men&eacute;.)</STAGE>
Oh! we are lo&s;t.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>All, all, is hopele&s;s.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>If he has Right in <HI>You</HI>, be &s;wift to <HI>own</HI> him:</L>
<L>Or, <HI>lo&s;e</HI> him by your Silence.</L>
<STAGE><HI>Offers to kill</HI> Eumenes.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Stay&mdash; he is &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Who? What?&mdash;&s;ay, quickly.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>He is <HI>My</HI> SON, <HI>Eumenes</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(&s;tarting, and a&s;ide.)</HI></STAGE>
'Tis as I <HI>fear'd</HI>; and all my Schemes are Air.</L>
<STAGE><HI>Stands pen&s;ively fix'd.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Gods!</HI>&mdash; Did I hear <HI>That</HI>, rightly?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(embracing him.)</HI></STAGE>
Thou <HI>art</HI> my Son.</L>
<L><HI>Cre&s;phontes</HI> was thy Father. I atte&s;t it:</L>
<L>I tell it, to the <HI>Winds:</HI> Proclaim it&mdash;boa&s;t it.</L>
<L>Hear it, <HI>Thou</HI> Soul of Murder! I have <HI>found</HI> him:</L>
<L>And, if I lo&s;e him, <HI>now</HI>, whole Heaven &s;hall <HI>cur&s;e</HI> thee.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I cannot comprehend it!&mdash;Yet, I kneel,</L>
<L>To <HI>thank</HI> you&mdash;but for deigning to <HI>deceive</HI> me.</L>
<L>Ble&s;s'd is his Fate, who dies, in &s;uch a <HI>Dream!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>One way, thou <HI>art</HI> deceiv'd. The Mother's Love</L>
<L>Forgets the Monarch's Danger.&mdash;<HI>Poliphontes!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="57" REF="60">
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE>[<HI>&s;tarting.</HI>]</STAGE>
Go on&mdash;I meditated&mdash;but&mdash; <HI>&s;peak</HI>, Madam.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Thou now ha&s;t wrung, from my affrighted Heart,</L>
<L>The <HI>Secret</HI>, that oppre&s;s'd it. Thou behold'&s;t</L>
<L>Thy <HI>King</HI>, di&s;tre&s;s'd, before thee. &mdash; <HI>Sigh</HI>, if thou can'&s;t,</L>
<L>Sigh,&mdash;for the Son, Prince, Mother&mdash;Fame, and Nature.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>How to re&s;olve will a&s;k &s;ome needful Pau&s;e.</L>
<L>&mdash;Mean while, it &s;hakes my Faith, to tru&s;t your Story.</L>
<L>You hear, the young Man's Hone&s;ty <HI>di&s;claims</HI></L>
<L>This Greatne&s;s, you wou'd lend him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Mode&s;t Sen&s;e</L>
<L>Of my unequal Worth compell'd &s;ome Doubting;</L>
<L>But, <HI>now</HI>, 'tis Truth conte&s;tle&s;s. Royal <HI>Tears</HI></L>
<L>Flow not for pitied <HI>Fal&s;ehood</HI>; and <HI>they</HI> prove it.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Tears touch not Hearts of <HI>Flint</HI>; and I will &s;pare 'em.</L>
<L>Bid your <NOTE N="*" PLACE="inter">kneels.</NOTE> <HI>Pride</HI> hear me&mdash;for, your Pity <HI>cannot</HI>.</L>
<L>See me an humble Supplicant, at your Feet,</L>
<L>Now fir&s;t confe&s;&s;ing I can <HI>fear</HI> your Anger.</L>
<L><HI>This</HI> &s;hou'd, beyond all Proof of Tears, <HI>convince</HI> you,</L>
<L>That <HI>Merop&eacute;</HI>'s his <HI>Mother</HI>.&mdash;Still you frown:</L>
<L>Forgetful of pa&s;t <HI>Soothings</HI>.&mdash;But&mdash;this Morning,</L>
<L><HI>You</HI>, cruel! <HI>You</HI>,&mdash;a&s;pir'd&mdash;to be his Father.</L>
<L>Once, he <HI>cou'd</HI> boa&s;t a Father!&mdash;how he <HI>lo&s;t</HI> him,</L>
<L>Heaven <HI>knows</HI>, howe'er it &s;peaks not!&mdash;I de&s;i&s;t</L>
<L>To <HI>a&s;k</HI>, that dreadful Secret. I forget</L>
<L>My own long Sorrows&mdash;all my Wrongs and In&s;ults:</L>
<L>Smile to the future&mdash;and ab&s;olve the pa&s;t.</L>
<L>&mdash;Let him <HI>but breathe</HI>&mdash;to reign, where to be <HI>wretched</HI>;</L>
<L>Where Kings, who dare live ju&s;t, mu&s;t die unhappy.</L>
<L>&mdash;Cruel! you an&s;wer nothing!&mdash;look le&s;s <HI>dreadful</HI>.</L>
<L>Hear with your <HI>Eyes</HI>, if your clos'd Ears are <HI>Iron</HI>.</L>
<L>Ea&s;e my di&s;tracted Soul&mdash;and &s;peak &s;ome <HI>Comfort</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="58" REF="61">
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>O, Madam, quit that <HI>Po&s;ture</HI>.&mdash;My proud Heart</L>
<L>A&s;pires to <HI>keep</HI> the Glory you have lent it.</L>
<L>&mdash;If I, indeed, was born, to call you Mother,</L>
<L>Why do I &s;ee and hear you, <HI>not</HI> a <HI>Queen?</HI></L>
<STAGE><HI>Rai&s;es her.</HI></STAGE>
<L>I know not, to what Rights a <HI>King</HI> is born:</L>
<L>But, &s;ure! he no where falls to le&s;s than <HI>greate&s;t</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;Nor think my Soul too haughty:&mdash;For <HI>What</HI> Scorn</L>
<L>Can treat the Proud, too proudly? No Di&s;tre&s;s</L>
<L>Ab&s;olves <HI>Dejection:</HI> 'Tis the Brave's <HI>Prerogative</HI>,</L>
<L>To feel, without <HI>complaining. Hercules</HI>,</L>
<L>Before He was a <HI>God</HI>, was, oft, <HI>unhappy</HI>.</L>
<L>What an unma&s;t'ring Monarch mu&s;t <HI>he</HI> make,</L>
<L>Who reigns not o'er <HI>Adv$r&s;ity!&mdash;Strike</HI>, Tyrant&mdash;</L>
<L>Courage, re&s;train'd from <HI>Act</HI>, takes Pride to <HI>&s;uffer</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE>[<HI>to</HI> Merop&eacute;.]</STAGE>
'Tis well. I have with ju&s;t Attention, heard;</L>
<L>And in impartial Silence, weigh'd it, all.</L>
<L><HI>Your Sorrow</HI> claims &s;ome Right to call for mine:</L>
<L>And <HI>his</HI> high <HI>Spirit</HI> charms me. I have mark'd</L>
<L>Each Movement of his Mind, and <HI>mu&s;t</HI> e&s;teem him.</L>
<L>&mdash;Yet further&mdash;I confe&s;s, he well <HI>de&s;erves</HI></L>
<L>To &s;hare the Blood of <HI>Kings:</HI> But, that he <HI>does</HI></L>
<L>Is either Fal&s;ehood, or a Truth &s;o doubtful,</L>
<L>As brooks no <HI>pa&s;&s;ion'd</HI> Evidence.&mdash;I take him</L>
<STAGE><HI>Takes</HI> Eumenes <HI>by the Hand</HI>.</STAGE>
<L>Into my heedful Care; remit his Sentence,</L>
<L>And, if found <HI>Yours</HI>, adopt him as my Son.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Yours</HI>, &s;aid you?&mdash;<HI>You!</HI> my Father!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! be patient.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>You</HI> rule his De&s;tiny. You know what Price</L>
<L>I rate his Life at. Smile; and meet my Wi&s;hes.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Inhuman Menacer!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Kind <HI>Love</HI> has &s;ent</L>
<L>This Youth, to &s;ave my Heart, from near De&s;pair.</L>
<L>Yours is too tenderly devoted <HI>His</HI>,</L>
<L>To an&s;wer with Imprudence. Weigh, and chu&s;e.</L>
<L>For, may the Gods, conjointly, cur&s;e my Reign.</L>
<L><PB N="59" REF="62">If he <HI>&s;urvives</HI> Refu&s;al of my Prayer!</L>
<L>&mdash;Bethink you. In an <HI>Hour</HI>, I &s;hall expect you;</L>
<L>Where, at the Altar, to th' atte&s;ting Powers,</L>
<L>You may proclaim your <HI>Choice</HI>. That Moment makes him</L>
<L>My <HI>Victim</HI>, or my <HI>Son</HI>. 'Till then, farewell.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>You <HI>cannot</HI> be &s;o cruel.&mdash;Leave <HI>him</HI>, with me.</L>
<L>To <HI>&s;ee</HI> him, might per&s;uade me.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>See him, <HI>there:</HI></L>
<L>See him, in <HI>Hymen</HI>'s <HI>Temple</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh, Queen! oh, Mother!</L>
<L>If I, already, dare a&s;&s;ume a Right</L>
<L>To call you, by that dear, that awful Name:</L>
<L><HI>Think</HI>, nothing, that may mi&s;become <HI>your</HI> Glory&mdash;</L>
<L><HI>Do</HI>, nothing, that may mix Contempt, with <HI>mine</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;I leave you to the Care of Heaven; and <HI>die</HI>.</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE>MEROP&Eacute;, EURICLES, ISMEN&Eacute;.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Fly, follow, <HI>Euricles!</HI> hold thy kind Eye</L>
<L>Fix'd, to this Mi&s;creant's Motions. Fain would I dream,</L>
<L>He threatens, but to fright me.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Willing Hope</L>
<L>So flatters, to deceive you. Too, too &s;ure,</L>
<L>His Purpo&s;e! Ev'n by Nature, &s;tern and bloody,</L>
<L>How <HI>more</HI>, when Power and Safety prompt his Cruelty!
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Euricles.</STAGE></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Find thy good Father: Ha&s;te <HI>I&s;men&eacute;</HI>; call him.</L>
<L>Tell him, Di&s;tre&s;s grows head&s;trong, and my Soul</L>
<L>Sickens, for want of Coun&s;el.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(a&s;ide.)</HI></STAGE>
What a Blindne&s;s</L>
<L>Is Thir&s;t of human Grandeur! Give me, Gods!</L>
<L>A Cottage, and Concealment. Save the Queen;</L>
<L>And, from the Cur&s;e of Courts, remotely place me.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> I&s;men&eacute;.</STAGE>
<SP>
<PB N="60" REF="63">
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(alone.)</HI></STAGE>
No, there is none; no Ruler of the Stars,</L>
<L>Regardful of my Mi&s;eries.&mdash;What Crime</L>
<L>Has drawn the&s;e Tortures on me?&mdash;I have been</L>
<L>Too in&s;olent, perhaps, in Youth's proud Joy;</L>
<L>And felt not, as I ought, for <HI>other</HI>'s Sorrows.</L>
<L>Thence, came this Tempe&s;t of Affliction o'er me,</L>
<L>And my &s;ucceeding Years have, all, been Horror.</L>
<L>Oh, my lov'd Son! my Eyes have lo&s;t thee, <HI>ever</HI>.</L>
<L>I &s;hall no more &s;natch Comfort, from thy Hopes,</L>
<L>Or wonder at thy Sweetne&s;s.&mdash;All thy <HI>Father</HI></L>
<L>Found me, <HI>again</HI>, in Thy renew'd Perfection;</L>
<L>And Death had given him back, with <HI>added Greatne&s;s</HI>.</L>
<L>Why have the Deities permitted this?</L>
<L>Why have they <HI>&s;ported</HI> with a Mortal's Mind,</L>
<L>Unpitying it's Di&s;traction? &s;ent him to me</L>
<L>From a far di&s;tant Land? Sent him, for what!</L>
<L>To glut the Murd'rer's <HI>Sword</HI>, who kill'd his Father.</L>
<L>&mdash;Yet, you are <HI>ju&s;t</HI>, ye Gods! &mdash; Amazing Darkne&s;s</L>
<L>Dwells o'er th' Eternal Will, and hides all <HI>Cau&s;e</HI>.</L>
<L>I mu&s;t not dare to tax Almighty Power,</L>
<L>For what I &s;uffer from it. Let it but <HI>pay</HI> me</L>
<L>With That curs'd Tyrant's <HI>Puni&s;hment</HI> attain'd:</L>
<L>Let me but &s;ee my&s;elf depriv'd of <HI>Him</HI>&mdash;</L>
<L>See him expell'd, from Light, from Earth, from Name,</L>
<L>Deep, as the chearle&s;s Voids below can plunge him!</L>
<L>And I will <NOTE PLACE="foot">(* kneeling.)</NOTE> kneel, a Wretch, and <HI>thank</HI> your Ju&s;tice.</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="61" REF="64">
<HEAD>SCENE IV.</HEAD>
<STAGE>MEROP&Eacute;, ISMEN&Eacute;, NARBAS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! Queen! be&s;t &s;hewn by Woes! What <HI>Wrongs</HI> are yours!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(ri&s;ing.)</HI></STAGE>
Yes, <HI>Narbas</HI>,&mdash;I <HI>have</HI> &s;acrific'd my Son&mdash;</L>
<L>Have given him up, to Death &mdash;have, madly, <HI>own'd</HI> him.</L>
<L>Yet, pity me, good <HI>Narbas!</HI>&mdash;Do not tell</L>
<L>Th' in&s;ulting <HI>World</HI>, this Weakne&s;s.&mdash;Nature <HI>knows</HI> it:</L>
<L>Knows, how Di&s;tre&s;s mi&s;leads: But In&s;ult does not.</L>
<L>&mdash;What Mother, who beheld her Son, as I did,</L>
<L>Doom'd and endanger'd, <HI>cou'd</HI> have, then, kept Silence!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Gen'rous your Purpo&s;e! gloriou&s;ly, you err'd:</L>
<L>And fell, but from a Height, 'twas Fam&euml;, to reach.</L>
<L>Dry up your Tears, and &s;ummon All your Soul:</L>
<L>Time pre&s;&s;es,&mdash;and a Moment, lo&s;t, is Fate.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Shouts heard.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(looking out.)</HI></STAGE>
Uproar, and Cries without, in ri&s;ing Wildne&s;s,</L>
<L>Heard from the City, reach the Palace Walls:</L>
<L>Sure Sign of new Confu&s;ion!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>From a Window,</L>
<L>Whence I look'd out, and mark'd the Streets below,</L>
<L>I &s;aw the Tyrant meet th' expecting <HI>Prie&s;ts</HI>;</L>
<L>Attending, <HI>not</HI> in <HI>Hymeneal</HI> Robes,</L>
<L>But Ve&s;tments, &s;uch as <HI>Sacrifice</HI> demands;</L>
<L>And Pomp of bloody Rites, at dreadful <HI>Altars</HI>.</L>
<L>To <HI>The&s;e</HI>, his Hand con&s;ign'd the Victim, led:</L>
<L><PB N="62" REF="65">And deaf'ning Shouts receiv'd him.&mdash;From the Train</L>
<L>Of Prie&s;tly Horrors, <HI>this Way</HI> mov'd their Chiefs;</L>
<L>Follow'd by loud, licentious, Bur&s;ts of Joy.</L>
<L>Amid th' enormous Swell of who&s;e coar&s;e Roar,</L>
<L>All, I di&s;tinctly heard was <HI>Poliphontes</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Yes, let 'em <HI>come</HI>&mdash;the&s;e Furies! <HI>rob'd</HI> in LYES!</L>
<L>White, as the Innocence they hate, <HI>without:</HI></L>
<L><HI>Within</HI>, more black than Night! more <HI>fell</HI>, than Death!</L>
<L>I will receive them, with their <HI>Tyrant</HI>'s Rage:</L>
<L>Meet, and o'erwhelm 'em &mdash; with a <HI>Mother</HI>'s Angui&s;h.</L>
<L>&mdash;Where are my <HI>Guards?</HI> Arm'd, for my Vengeance, call 'em.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Soldiers enter, on one Side: On the other, three Prie&s;ts.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE V.</HEAD>
<STAGE>MEROP&Eacute;, NARBAS, ISMEN&Eacute;, PRIESTS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What! are ye here already?&mdash;Out of my Sight,</L>
<L>Ye &s;anctify'd <HI>Deceits!</HI> You! who&s;e bold Arts</L>
<L>Rule Rulers! and would fright even <HI>Kings</HI>, to <HI>Awe!</HI></L>
<L>Be gone, fly, vani&s;h&mdash;Or the <HI>Death</HI>, you bring</L>
<L>For Virtue, overtakes your puni&s;h'd <HI>Guilt</HI>.</L>
<L>Ye Mouths of Mercy! and ye Ha$ds of Blood!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Chief Prie&s;t.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Sorrows, and Wrongs, claim Privilege to <HI>rail:</HI></L>
<L>And Heaven's affronted <HI>Vot'ries</HI> mu&s;t <HI>forgive</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Cool</HI>, in your Cruelty!&mdash;Religion's Veil</L>
<L>Ill cloaks Rebellion's Licence. <HI>Death</HI> was your Errand.</L>
<L>Why talk you of <HI>Forgivene&s;s?</HI>&mdash;'tis not yours.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="63" REF="66">
<SPEAKER><HI>Chief Prie&s;t.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Not in <HI>Death</HI>'s Cau&s;e we come; but Heaven's &mdash; and <HI>Love</HI>'s.</L>
<L>If <HI>Vows</HI> were plighted, 'twixt the <HI>King</HI> and <HI>You</HI>,</L>
<L>No Power on Earth di&s;&s;olves 'em.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Fal&s;e, as Hell!</L>
<L>He knows, I heard his hated Vows with Horror.</L>
<L>Slight In&s;olence!&mdash; To <HI>this</HI> ill founded Charge,</L>
<L>Silence, and Scorn, &s;hall an&s;wer.
<STAGE><HI>turning away.</HI></STAGE></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Chief Prie&s;t.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Gracious Sovereign!</L>
<L>Su&s;pend your Anger: 'tis unju&s;tly rais'd.</L>
<L>&mdash; Enlighten, and <HI>command</HI> us. &mdash; Found too <HI>ea&s;y</HI></L>
<L>In one <HI>wrong'd</HI> Faith, we twice, perhaps, have <HI>e$r'd:</HI></L>
<L>A like deceiv'd, in <HI>Both</HI>. &mdash; Unbend that Brow:</L>
<L>And deign to teach our Doubt, what <HI>Name</HI> to give</L>
<L>This Stranger? this young Captive to the King?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Give him the Name you dare to mi&s;apply.</L>
<L>Call him your <HI>King</HI>&mdash;my Son&mdash;my lo&s;t <HI>Eumenes</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Chief Prie&s;t.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Hear <HI>That</HI>, prophetic Soul! high</L>
<L>Heaven!&mdash;I tremble,</L>
<L>In Dread, this great Di&s;covery comes too late.</L>
<L>The &s;houting People crowd the waiting Altar:</L>
<L>And, erring in their Zeal, <HI>mi&s;-hail</HI> the Day.</L>
<L>&mdash;What <HI>can</HI> be, &s;hall be try'd, to cro&s;s his Doom.</L>
<L>They &s;hall be taught, in bold, adventrous Whi&s;pers,</L>
<L>To &s;ave their Sovereign's Right&mdash; but, hence, ra&s;h Queen?</L>
<L>Learn due Repentance: and no more, let loo&s;e</L>
<L>The Wrongs of Rage, again&s;t the <HI>Tongues</HI> of <HI>Gods</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt Prie&s;ts.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<LG>
<L>Corrected Pa&s;&s;ion, reverent Hope, touch'd Shame,</L>
<L>And All a Mother's <HI>Fears</HI>, divide my Heart,</L>
<L><PB N="64" REF="67">&mdash; This &s;olemn Sharpne&s;s of de&s;erv'd Reproach,</L>
<L>Mildly maje&s;tic, and &s;everely &s;oft,</L>
<L>Struck my too con&s;cious Guilt, with infelt Awe!</L>
<L>I have been warm too &s;oon: and ju&s;t, too late.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>What, tho' Religion's <HI>Guardians</HI> taint her Tide!</L>
<L>Pure is the <HI>Fountain</HI>, tho' the Stream flows <HI>wide</HI></L>
<L>Too oft, her <HI>erring Guides</HI> her Cau&s;e, betray:</L>
<L>Yet, Rage grows <HI>impious</HI>, when it <HI>bars</HI> her <HI>Way</HI>.</L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER><HI>The End of the</HI> FOURTH ACT.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="act">
<PB N="65" REF="68">
<HEAD>ACT V.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>A Pri&s;on.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>EUMENES. NARBAS. EURICLES.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>EUMENES.</SPEAKER>
<L>NOW, recollect your Danger: fly, lov'd Father!</L>
<L>Think on the Tyrant's Power, and &s;hun his Rage.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>All Sen&s;e of my own Danger lo&s;t, in yours,</L>
<L>I threw my&s;elf, regardle&s;s, at his Feet,</L>
<L>Full of the fatal Subject, I began,</L>
<L>Uncautious in my Tran&s;port. Starting Con&s;cience</L>
<L><HI>Fled</HI> from the Face of Truth. He &s;hun'd to <HI>heer</HI>,</L>
<L>Broke &s;hort, reply'd, 'twas well: gave me Permi&s;&s;ion;</L>
<L>Nay, full of &s;eeming Zeal, <HI>injoin'd</HI> my coming&mdash;</L>
<L>Bad me go pay my <HI>la&s;t</HI> &s;hort Debt, of Coun&s;el:</L>
<L>And try to bend your Heart, to meet his Will.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>He added, that his <HI>Queen</HI>&mdash; he called her <HI>His!</HI></L>
<L>I blu&s;h to name her &s;uch: but &s;o, he charg'd me.</L>
<L>Since <HI>&s;he</HI>, he &s;aid, in Pity but for you,</L>
<L>Yields a reluctant Hand, to clo&s;e with <HI>his</HI>,</L>
<L>'Tis Time, <HI>her Son</HI>, who&s;e Life &s;he holds &s;o dear,</L>
<L>Aids his own Int're&s;t, and confirms <HI>her</HI> Safety.</L>
<L>&mdash; The Re&s;t, he paus'd and thought: but held it in,</L>
<L>Di&s;dainf$l, frown'd a Nod &mdash; and bad us <HI>have</HI> him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="66" REF="69">
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Slowly awaking, from my Dream of Wonders,</L>
<L>I &s;eem re-born, to &s;ome new World, unknown;</L>
<L>Where every thing, I meet with, &s;hocks my Soul.</L>
<L>New Blood in&s;pires me! a new Nature prompts me!</L>
<L>And a new, <HI>gloomy Daylight</HI> dims my Views.</L>
<L>&mdash;You talk of <HI>dying</HI>, whil&s;t I, yet, half doubt,</L>
<L>Whether, exi&s;ting now, I really <HI>live!</HI></L>
<L>If I am, truly, the lo&s;t Wretch I <HI>&s;eem</HI>,</L>
<L>If here, confe&s;s'd, I <HI>claim</HI> this Birth &s;ublime,</L>
<L>If in <HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI> now inclos'd, I find</L>
<L>Queen <HI>Merop&eacute;</HI>, my Mother&mdash;King <HI>Cre&s;phontes</HI></L>
<L>My Father murder'd&mdash;his fear'd Murd'rer crown'd,</L>
<L>With his &s;tol'n Diadem: and, in it, daring</L>
<L>Offer his widow'd Queen a <HI>Hand</HI>, &s;tain'd, frightful,</L>
<L>In her fir&s;t <HI>Hu&s;band</HI>'s <HI>Blood</HI>&mdash;All This, to <HI>me!</HI></L>
<L>Seems, while I drink <HI>in</HI> Heaven's fair Light, and view</L>
<L>You Man&s;ion of the <HI>Gods</HI>, who govern Man&mdash;</L>
<L>Incredible! a&s;toni&s;hing! &mdash; and horrid!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Tis horrible, indeed! too dark for Thought!</L>
<L>&mdash;But, Rea&s;on's Line wants <HI>Depth</HI> to &s;ound Heaven's Will.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Deign, my <HI>devoted</HI> Prince! my King!&mdash; my <HI>Son!</HI></L>
<L>Suffer me, &s;till, to u&s;e that long-lov'd Name&mdash;</L>
<L>Deign but&mdash;to <HI>live</HI>.&mdash;Time, Chance, and Fortune's Changes,</L>
<L>May vindicate your Glory.&mdash;Since the Tyrant</L>
<L>Tempts, to <HI>betray</HI> &mdash; reward him, with his <HI>own</HI>.</L>
<L>Deceive Deceivers, and Deceit grows <HI>Virtue</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>This</HI>, in thy Fore&s;ts, <HI>Elis!</HI> had I heard,</L>
<L>Even there, I &s;hou'd have blu&s;h'd to hear, from <HI>Narbas!</HI></L>
<L>But, as I am.&mdash;No more.&mdash;I would not wrong</L>
<L><PB N="67" REF="70">Virtue, &s;o <HI>try'd</HI>, by the lea&s;t Shade of Doubt.</L>
<L>Undue Su&s;picion is more abject Ba&s;ene&s;s,</L>
<L>Even than the Guilt &s;u&s;pected. &mdash;Pardon the <HI>&s;eeming</HI>.</L>
<L>Kind was your <HI>Motive!</HI>&mdash;pitying my <HI>Di&s;tre&s;s</HI>,</L>
<L>You, but, forgot my <HI>Duty</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Happy</HI> Fore&s;ts!</L>
<L>Wou'd, Ye were Ours, once more! there, Peace dwelt with us:</L>
<L>There, Safety &s;lept, upon unguarded Hills,</L>
<L>And every Tree's &s;oft Shadow <HI>cover'd</HI> Angui&s;h.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Erring</HI>, from Shade to Shade, there, lo&s;t to Glory,</L>
<L>Deaf, to my&mdash;Parent's Wrongs, my Country's Call,</L>
<L>The Great Man's Virtues, or the Good Man's Duties,</L>
<L>I lay, and langui&s;h'd out a deedle&s;s Youth:</L>
<L>Ea&s;y too early; yet, in Re&s;t, un&s;atisfied!</L>
<L>Something, like In&s;tinct, wak'd Alarm, within me.</L>
<L>Something, I felt at heart &mdash; I knew not what &mdash;</L>
<L>Withdrew me from this Calm! &mdash; I wanted Nothing:</L>
<L>Yet, Nothing, I po&s;&s;e&s;s'd, cou'd fill my Mind!</L>
<L>What was it I pur&s;ued, which you not <HI>gave</HI> me?</L>
<L>I weigh'd your Worth, and cou'd not <HI>wi&s;h</HI> it <HI>more:</HI></L>
<L>Even to your <HI>Wants</HI>, I <HI>lov'd</HI>&mdash;whate'er was yours;</L>
<L>And rev'renc'd your Afflictions. Witne&s;s, Heaven!</L>
<L>I never wou'd have wi&s;h'd a <HI>nobler</HI> Father.</L>
<L>&mdash;The Heaven I have atte&s;ted, found it fit</L>
<L>To <HI>give</HI> me One, una&s;k'd: and made me <HI>wretched</HI>.</L>
<L>I find That Father, lo&s;t to Life, and Empire&mdash;</L>
<L>I find a Mother, wrong'd&mdash;and cannot right her&mdash;</L>
<L>I find a <HI>People</HI> mine&mdash;yet, find <HI>my&s;elf</HI></L>
<L><PB N="68" REF="71">The Slave of their Oppre&s;&s;or.&mdash;Oh! ye Gods!</L>
<L>Is This, to be a <HI>King!</HI>&mdash;why <HI>wou'd</HI> you &s;ave me?</L>
<L>Why, with mi&s;taken Goodne&s;s, wou'd your Love</L>
<L>Per&s;uade me, to <HI>&s;u&s;tain</HI>, a Life, &s;o curs'd?</L>
<L>Why did your ill-tim'd Aid <HI>avert</HI> the Stroke,</L>
<L>That wou'd have left this dreadful Scene <HI>un|drawn</HI>,</L>
<L>And plung'd me into one long Sleep, of Peace?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! 'tis too <HI>near</HI>, that Sleep!&mdash;the Tyrant <HI>comes!</HI></L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>POLIPHONTES. <HI>To the Fore-going.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Retire: and wait, without.</L>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt</HI> Euricles <HI>and</HI> Narbas.</STAGE>
<L>&mdash;And Thou, ra&s;h Youth!</L>
<L>Who&s;e unexperienc'd Years, and gen'rous Plain|ne&s;s,</L>
<L>Fill me with all the Pity, due to Weakne&s;s!</L>
<L>For the la&s;t Time I come, to bring thee Power</L>
<L>Thy&s;elf, to chu&s;e, and <HI>make</HI>, thy Form of For|tune.</L>
<L>Thy <HI>pre&s;ent</HI>, and thy future,&mdash;thy claim'd Birth,</L>
<L>Fate, Figure, Being,&mdash;all,&mdash;depend on <HI>me</HI>,</L>
<L>&mdash;What has gay Youth like thine to do with <HI>State?</HI></L>
<L>Eyele&s;s and dark, amid the gloomy Wilds:</L>
<L>Of Court Intrigue, thou <HI>want'&s;t</HI> the Torch, of Time,</L>
<L>To light thee, through the mazy <HI>Curves</HI>, of Power;</L>
<L>Or, burn <HI>Ob&s;truction</HI>'s Fabricks down before thee.</L>
<L>Leave to <HI>my</HI> Toil, to &s;mooth thy future Paths;</L>
<L><PB N="69" REF="72">And root out Faction's Thorns, which trouble Empire.</L>
<L>&mdash;When I am <HI>dead</HI>&mdash;as Age admits <HI>&s;hort</HI> Stay,</L>
<L>Thou, and my <HI>Merop&eacute;</HI> will reign, at Ea&s;e,</L>
<L>And thank my painful Cares: and love my Me|mory.</L>
<L>&mdash;Why art thou dumb?&mdash;Pau&s;e on&mdash;I read thee rightly.</L>
<L>Thou ha&s;t, I know, a kind of &s;tuborn Pride,</L>
<L>Call'd <HI>Courage</HI>&mdash;and mi&s;tak'&s;t it, for a <HI>Virtue</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;<HI>'Tis</HI> Virtue; when Pre&s;umption drives it not:</L>
<L>But &s;uffers <HI>Thought</HI> to guide it.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Guiding Thought</L>
<L>Has held me patient, long.&mdash;Now, an&s;wer <HI>me</HI>.</L>
<L>Am I <HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI>'s <HI>Monarch?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>For thy Birth,</L>
<L>Be it, as Truth, or Trick, or Chance, conclude it,</L>
<L>If, from &s;ome low, &s;ome namele&s;s Stock, de|rived,</L>
<L>Be humble, and advis'd&mdash;and ri&s;e to Greatne&s;s.</L>
<L>If happier Offspring ca&s;t thee for a <HI>King</HI>,</L>
<L>Make thy&s;elf <HI>worthy</HI>, of the Crown I mean thee.</L>
<L>&mdash;'Tis but, to wait me to the Marriage Altar,</L>
<L>Where Love, and <HI>Merop&eacute;</HI>, and Peace, attend.</L>
<L>There, to the Gods and me,
<STAGE>[<HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI>'s <HI>Guardians</HI>.]</STAGE></L>
<L>Swear Homage, and devote thy faithful Sword.</L>
<L>That done, Sports, Joys, and Safety crown thy Youth:</L>
<L>And, in thy riper Years, expect the Diadem.</L>
<L>&mdash; Determine.&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Tis determin'd.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Tell me <HI>how?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Why am I left <HI>unfree</HI> to <HI>chu&s;e</HI>&mdash;yet, pre&s;s'd</L>
<L>To tell thee my Deci&s;ion?&mdash;The <HI>compell'd</HI></L>
<L>To <HI>yield</HI>, di&s;grace Con&s;ent: and make Faith doubt|ful.</L>
<L>Kings &s;hou'd di&s;dain to dread their <HI>powerful</HI> Foes:</L>
<L><PB N="70" REF="73">Le&s;s &s;hou'd they deign, to &s;well the Pride of <HI>weak</HI> ones.</L>
<L>&mdash;I am a <HI>Captive</HI>. He, who holds not Freedom,</L>
<L>Has not his Will his <HI>own:</HI>&mdash;and chu&s;es <HI>no|thing</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Fierce, amid Mi&s;ery! thou, at once, art brave,</L>
<L>And in&s;olent, and wretched!&mdash; but, beware,</L>
<L>Nor tru&s;t, too far, my Pity of thy Poorne&s;s.</L>
<L>I give thee, yet, &s;ome Moments, to re&s;olve.</L>
<L>I go, before thee: but, my Guards attend,</L>
<L>To bring thee to the Altar. Come, determin'd</L>
<L>To <HI>&s;wear</HI>&mdash;and hope my Crown, and live, my Son:</L>
<L>Or <HI>die</HI>, a Slave un-own'd, and lo&s;e thy <HI>Name</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Is going.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(calling after him.)</HI></STAGE>
Thou <HI>goe&s;t</HI> then?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(Stopping.)</HI></STAGE>
To <HI>expect</HI> thee.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I will <HI>come</HI>.</L>
<L>And <HI>with</HI> me, (tremble to be told it,) comes</L>
<L>The <HI>God</HI>, that rais'd <HI>my</HI> Race to root out <HI>Tyrants</HI>.</L>
<L>For <HI>Thee</HI>, proud Troubler of a pilfer'd <HI>Hour!</HI></L>
<L>Whom <HI>Age</HI> and <HI>Guilt</HI> combine to &s;hake from Em|pire!</L>
<L><HI>Soon</HI> &s;hall the Throne thou <HI>&s;tol'&s;t</HI> no more be Thine:</L>
<L>And every &s;naky Fury <HI>hi&s;s</HI> to <HI>find</HI> thee.</L>
<L>Horror and Penitence &s;hall <HI>pale</HI> tho&s;e <HI>Eyes</HI>,</L>
<L>Which, in&s;olently ardent, <HI>frown</HI> on <HI>Virtue</HI>.</L>
<L>Menace and In&s;ult, <HI>then</HI>, &s;hall quit thy <HI>Voice</HI>,</L>
<L>And groaning <HI>Angui&s;h</HI> grind it.&mdash;What the Gods</L>
<L>Re&s;train <HI>my</HI> Hand from reaching, <HI>happier</HI> Sons</L>
<L>Of my <HI>immortal Sire</HI> &s;hall ri&s;e, to execute:</L>
<L>And hurl thee from a <HI>Power</HI>, that <HI>hurts Man|kind</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Pol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Here, <HI>Narbas! Euricles!</HI>&mdash;You may return.</L>
<L><PB N="71" REF="74">I leave him to your Le&s;&s;ons. Too too deeply,</L>
<L>He feels their pa&s;t Impre&s;&s;ion. Teach him better:</L>
<L>Or your exacted <HI>Heads</HI> &s;hall an&s;wer to me,</L>
<L>For every well-known Help I owe your Hatred.</L>
<L>&mdash;<HI>Narbas!</HI> Thy Age, I think, might be&s;t be tru&s;ted.</L>
<L>Experience lays his Dangers open to thee.</L>
<L>Thou, as thou lov'&s;t, advi&s;e him.&mdash; Whether born</L>
<L>The Son of <HI>Merop&eacute;</HI>, or <HI>Thine</HI>, no matter.</L>
<L>I mu&s;t adopt him mine,&mdash;or <HI>Death</HI> demands him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Away,&mdash;Even to the <HI>Soul, E$m$nes</HI> dies,</L>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Poliphontes.</STAGE>
<L>Ere <HI>Thine</HI>, but for a Moment. &mdash; Friends! did you <HI>hear</HI> him?</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE>EUM$MES, NARBAS, EURICLES.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Where</HI> did this ill-in&s;tructed Tyrant learn</L>
<L>To <HI>threaten</HI>, for Per&s;ua&s;ion!&mdash;I &s;u&s;pect,</L>
<L>He does not <HI>&s;eem</HI> to doubt, but <HI>doubts indeed</HI></L>
<L>I &s;hare no Blood of <HI>Hercules</HI>.&mdash;He's gone:</L>
<L>And call'd me, to his Altar.&mdash;Let us <HI>follow</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Pau&s;e.&mdash;Whither wou'd &s;uch fatal Ra&s;h|ne&s;s lead you?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>The Queen has Friends: howe'er too weak, too few:</L>
<L>Who dare <HI>defend</HI> her Cau&s;e. Give us but <HI>Time</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>In a &s;erener, <HI>&s;afer</HI>, Hour, than <HI>This</HI>,</L>
<L>How gladly had my Heart obey'd your Coun&s;el!</L>
<L>Tru&s;ted your Wi&s;dom! heard with docile Ear!</L>
<L>And will'd but by <HI>your</HI> Guidance!&mdash;As it <HI>is</HI>,</L>
<L>I dare not hazard a Friend's <HI>Fall</HI>, to &s;ave me.</L>
<L>No.&mdash;In an Hour &s;o black, &s;o dire, as This,</L>
<L><PB N="72" REF="75">I ta&s;k but my own Heart, and <HI>Heaven</HI>, to aid me.</L>
<L>If I <HI>mu&s;t</HI> fall, I <HI>will</HI>. &mdash;I go &mdash; to <HI>try</HI></L>
<L>What <HI>God</HI> for&s;akes the Friendle&s;s.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Going out, meets</HI> Merop&eacute;.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="4" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE IV.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MEROP&Eacute;.</SPEAKER>
<L>Stay, my Son.&mdash;</L>
<L>Th' U&s;urper &s;ends me to thee.&mdash;Re&s;t, un|heard,</L>
<L><HI>His</HI> Errand: but my own requires thy Ear.</L>
<L>It has, perhaps, been told thee, that the <HI>Woman</HI></L>
<L>Conquers the <HI>Queen:</HI> and, that pervertive Dread</L>
<L>Of the Son's Fate forgets the Mother's <HI>Duty</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;Let no light <HI>Credit</HI> of a Guilt &s;o &s;hameful</L>
<L>In&s;ult the Daughter, Mother, Wife,&mdash;ah, me!</L>
<L>And <HI>Widow</HI>&mdash;of a King.&mdash;Yet, I <HI>mu&s;t</HI> go:</L>
<L>Mu&s;t, at the Altar, lend my trembling <HI>Hand</HI>;</L>
<L>And <HI>&s;eem</HI>&mdash;oh, Heaven! &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Seem</HI>, Madam?&mdash;&s;o, to &s;eem,</L>
<L>Were &s;o to <HI>be</HI>. Can &s;olemn Vows, at Altars,</L>
<L>Leave Room for Art's Eva&s;ions? See <HI>me</HI>, &s;ooner,</L>
<L>Tinge-ing the &s;potted Stone with blu&s;hing Blood:</L>
<L>And my torn <HI>Brea&s;t</HI> the offer'd Sacrifice.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>So look'd, &s;o &s;poke&mdash;&s;o &s;ometimes, frown'd, <HI>Cre&s;phontes</HI>.</L>
<L>Full of thy godlike Father, copy too,</L>
<L>The <HI>Confidence</HI>, he lent me. <HI>He</HI> had &s;corn'd</L>
<L>To doubt me, for a Moment, <HI>le&s;s than Merop&eacute;</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>If I was guilty,&mdash;think&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>&mdash;Be dumb.&mdash;Time pre&s;&s;es;&mdash;</L>
<L>Hear my re&s;olving Will: and curb thy own.</L>
<L>Th' U&s;urper of thy Throne no &s;ooner joins</L>
<L>My Hand's &s;uppos'd Con&s;ent, than, at the <HI>Altar</HI>,</L>
<L>He <HI>&s;wears</HI>&mdash;in all the Pomp of <HI>prie&s;tly Witne&s;s</HI>,</L>
<L><PB N="73" REF="76">To free thee from thy Chains&mdash;and, from That Hour,</L>
<L>Confirm <HI>Succe&s;&s;ion</HI>, thine.&mdash;So, &s;uffers <HI>Thee</HI>,</L>
<L>(By Heav'n's whole imprecated Ho&s;t, he <HI>&s;wears</HI> it)</L>
<L>To <HI>live</HI>, till he's no more; then, reign, a King.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Think, at what <HI>Price</HI> comes Empire, bought &s;o <HI>dear!</HI></L>
<L>Rather than &s;ee you wed him &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Ra&s;h, again?&mdash;</L>
<L><HI>Bound</HI>, by an Oath, &s;o witne&s;s'd, by the <HI>Gods</HI>,</L>
<L>And All <HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI>'s <HI>Prie&s;ts</HI>&mdash;and All her <HI>Peers</HI>&mdash;</L>
<L>He dares not <HI>break</HI> it: and Thou liv'&s;t to <HI>reign</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;For me, who have, thenceforth, no Call for Life,</L>
<L>I &s;eek thy <HI>Father</HI>, in the Glooms, below.</L>
<L>Triumphant, in the Point of la&s;t Di&s;tre&s;s.</L>
<L>Even when the Good &s;hall pity, Bad &s;hall &s;corn me,</L>
<L>When Honour dreams me <HI>fall'n</HI>, below Redre&s;s;</L>
<L>Then, &s;hall this forfeit Hand, di&s;daining Ba&s;e|ne&s;s,</L>
<L>Brighter than Glory &s;hine, in prais'd Atonement:</L>
<L>And mock the Tyrant's Hope, and &s;hun his In&s;ult.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Death, in a thou&s;and Shapes, compar'd with This,</L>
<L>Smiles, with an Infant's Innocence.&mdash;No more.</L>
<L>&mdash;It &s;hall <HI>not be</HI>.&mdash;See! my repugnant Soul</L>
<L>Shrinks from th' abhorr'd Conce&s;&s;ion. The felt <HI>God</HI>,</L>
<L>The GOD, glows, in me: &s;wells, again&s;t Con|troul:</L>
<L>And every &s;pringy Nerve is active <HI>Fire!</HI></L>
<L>Come on, Friends! Father! Mother! &mdash;tru&s;t my Firmne&s;s,</L>
<L>Tru&s;t it in Death's dire Scorn. Come, ha&s;ten with me&mdash;</L>
<L><HI>See</HI>, if I bear a Heart, that brooks this Wrong:</L>
<L>That poorly pants, for a ba&s;e Hour of <HI>Life</HI>&mdash;</L>
<L><PB N="74" REF="77">And lets a <HI>Woman</HI>'s Blood outdare a <HI>King</HI>'s.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Going.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! &s;tay: return.&mdash;Call: &s;top him.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Sir!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Prince!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Son!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><STAGE><HI>(Returning.)</HI></STAGE>
Look out: hark yonder: from my Father's <HI>Tomb</HI>.</L>
<L>Hear! his <HI>Gho&s;t</HI> calls!&mdash;Wrong'd Spirit! I <HI>obey</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! &s;tay, one Moment, <HI>&s;tay</HI>.&mdash;Methinks the <HI>God</HI></L>
<L>He talk'd of, &s;wells <HI>indeed</HI>, his widening Soul!</L>
<L>Lifts him, <HI>above</HI> Him&s;elf&mdash;above <HI>Mankind</HI>.</L>
<L>I will, re&s;pectful, <HI>hail</HI> the Power Divine:</L>
<L>And hope, beyond Appearance.&mdash;Yet, oh! hear me!</L>
<L>Oh! &s;peak to me, <HI>Eumenes!</HI>&mdash;ere thou goe&s;t,</L>
<L>Breathe on my di&s;tant Heart &s;ome Beam&mdash;&s;ome Share&mdash;</L>
<L>Of this in&s;pir'd Divinity, that &s;hakes thee.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Come&mdash;let me lead you to the Altar's Foot.</L>
<L><HI>There</HI> hear, there, &s;ee&mdash;<HI>there</HI>, dwells th' Eternal's Eye!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Ah! what is thy De&s;ign!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>To <HI>die</HI>,&mdash;to <HI>live</HI>.</L>
<L>Friends!&mdash;in this warm Embrace, <HI>divide</HI> my Soul.</L>
<L>Farewel!&mdash;farewel, <HI>for ever</HI>.</L>
<STAGE><HI>To</HI> Narbas, <HI>who pre&s;&s;es him tenderly</HI>.</STAGE>
<L>&mdash;Weep not, my Father!</L>
<L>No Blu&s;h, for Deeds unworthy your In&s;tructions,</L>
<L>Shall &s;tain Remembrance of the Care, I co&s;t you.</L>
<L>&mdash;Stay, <HI>you</HI>&mdash;till hither this good Lord, return|ing,</L>
<L>May guide your Purpo&s;e: or require your Coun|&s;el.</L>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Eumenes.</STAGE>
<STAGE><PB N="75" REF="78">Merop&eacute; <HI>to</HI> I&s;men&eacute;, <HI>who enters</HI>.</STAGE>
<L><HI>I&s;men&eacute;!</HI> &s;tay: comfort thy mournful Father.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt</HI> Merop&eacute; <HI>and</HI> Euricles.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="5" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE V.</HEAD>
<STAGE>NARBAS, ISMEN&Eacute;.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Away&mdash;I wou'd not &s;ee <HI>thee</HI> &s;hare my Sorrow.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Oh! 'twere too <HI>poor</HI> a Wi&s;h. Heaven knows, I &s;eek</L>
<L>No <HI>Share</HI>, I long for <HI>Power</HI>, to bear it, <HI>All</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Thou art too good, for Courts&mdash;where <HI>Ruin</HI> preys</L>
<L>On Innocence; and nought but <HI>Guile</HI> is &s;afe.</L>
<L>&mdash;What are thy Thoughts, of this lo&s;t <HI>Prince</HI>'s Virtues?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I am un&s;kill'd in Man: and, mo&s;t, in Kings.</L>
<L>But, &s;ure! if ever Beauty dwelt in Form,</L>
<L>Courage in Gentlene&s;s, or Truth in Grandeur,</L>
<L>All tho&s;e adorn'd Di&s;tinctions meet, in <HI>Him</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Yet, &s;ee! how Heaven, that <HI>gave</HI> him all the&s;e Claims,</L>
<L>Forgets 'em, and re&s;igns him.&mdash;Let That teach thee,</L>
<L>When, &s;oon, as &s;oon they will, thy Splendors <HI>fall</HI>,</L>
<L>Thou lo&s;e&s;t nothing, but a Right to <HI>Woes:</HI></L>
<L>Which <HI>mean</HI> Maids never meet with.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Shou'd the Queen,</L>
<L>Be&s;t, of her Sex! and Great, above all Rank!</L>
<L>Leave this loud Stage of Pain,&mdash;and re&s;t in <HI>Death</HI>,</L>
<L>Oh! teach my willing Feet to find &s;ome Gloom,</L>
<L>Dark, as my Pro&s;pects, deep inclos'd, for Safety;</L>
<L>And &s;ilent, as the Brow of midnight Sleep!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>And cou'd&s;t thou, &s;o, have <HI>Courage</HI>, to be &s;afe?&mdash;</L>
<L>Yes, we <HI>will</HI> go, my <HI>&s;weet I&s;men&eacute;</HI>, go,</L>
<L>Where Sorrow's &s;harpe&s;t Eye &s;hall fail to find us.</L>
<L><PB N="76" REF="79">Where we may mix with Men, who ne'er de|ceiv'd,</L>
<L>And Women, born to <HI>be</HI>, the Charms they look.</L>
<L>&mdash;There <HI>is</HI> a Place, which my <HI>Eumenes</HI> lov'd,</L>
<L>Till Youth's fond Hope of Glory da&s;h'd his Peace;</L>
<L>Where Nature, plainly noble, knows no <HI>Pomp:</HI></L>
<L>And Virtue moves no <HI>Envy:</HI>&mdash; quite <HI>Plenty</HI>,</L>
<L>Unartful <HI>Plea&s;ure</HI>, unaffected <HI>Joy</HI>,</L>
<L>And ever blu&s;hing, ever guiltle&s;s <HI>Mode&s;ty</HI>,</L>
<L>Cloathe Love, and Ta&s;te, and Conver&s;e, neatly fine:</L>
<L>Unloaded with their <HI>Tin&s;els</HI>.&mdash;Hark! That <HI>Cry</HI></L>
<L>Bodes Horror&mdash;'tis the Signal of &s;ome Fate,</L>
<L>&mdash;Li&s;ten, again&mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Again I hear: and tremble.</L>
<L>Who knows, but, now, the Queen's too direful Deed</L>
<L>Has ended all her Mis'ries!&mdash;Cruel <HI>Hymen!</HI></L>
<L>Such if thy Unions, let the World <HI>disjoin!</HI></L>
<L>And Marriage be the hated Mark of Shame!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>No more the&s;e Eyes &s;hall find thee, fated King!</L>
<L><HI>Cre&s;phontes</HI>, and his Race, are, All, no more.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Hark! It comes on, like Thunder in the Wind,</L>
<L>Still &s;trength'ning in its Motion.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>I di&s;tingui&s;h</L>
<L>The Voice of battling Parties&mdash;echoing Trum|pets&mdash;</L>
<L>And Groans of dying Men, confus'dly mingled.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>(at a Window.)</HI> Hence, from the Temple, to the Palace Gate,</L>
<L>The &s;cattring Crowd runs, wide, a thou&s;and Ways:</L>
<L>All bu&s;ied, without View&mdash;All, driven, by Terror!</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="6" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="77" REF="80">
<HEAD>SCENE VI.</HEAD>
<STAGE>NARBAS. ISMEN&Eacute;. EURICLES, <HI>bloody</HI>.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Breathle&s;s and bleeding &s;ee! who comes!</L>
<L>&mdash;O, <HI>Euricles!</HI></L>
<L>Is it of Enemies?&mdash;or, flows it, fatal?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Now would the Deaf be ble&s;s'd&mdash;the Blind be happy.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Scarce had I Strength, wedg'd in by cro&s;|&s;ing Crowds,</L>
<L>To &s;tem you breathing Torrent.&mdash;Give me Re&s;t.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L><HI>Eumenes?</HI>&mdash; does he <HI>live?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>He. &mdash;</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Dreadful Pau&s;e!</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>He is&mdash; the <HI>Son confe&s;s'd</HI>&mdash;of <HI>Grecian Gods!</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>What has he &s;uffer'd?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Nothing&mdash;but, has <HI>done</HI> &mdash;</L>
<L>Beyond Example's Boa&s;t&mdash;Oh! &s;uch a Deed!</L>
<L>So terrible! &s;o ju&s;t!&mdash;&s;o fill'd with Wonders!</L>
<L>That half <HI>Alcides</HI>' Labours, &s;carce were more.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>And &s;hall he be a King?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>He <HI>is</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>And <HI>Merop&eacute;?</HI></L>
<L>Great Mirror of Affliction! &mdash;lives <HI>She</HI>, too?</L>
<L>How was it?&mdash;&s;ay.&mdash;My Joys will grow too &s;trong?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>The Altar, &s;trew'd with Flow'rs, was ready dre&s;s'd,</L>
<L>The &s;moking Incen&s;e ro&s;e, in fragrant Curls,</L>
<L>And <HI>Hymen</HI>'s lambent Torches flam'd, &s;erene,</L>
<L>Silence and Expectation's dreadful <HI>Stillne&s;s</HI>,</L>
<L>Doubled the &s;olemn Horror of the Scene!</L>
<L>&mdash;There, <HI>Poliphontes</HI> &s;tood: and, at his Side,</L>
<L>Dumb as a de&s;tin'd Victim, &s;tood the <HI>Queen</HI>.</L>
<L>Our Prince's &s;ummon'd Hand had touch'd the Altar;</L>
<L><PB N="78" REF="81">His Eye &s;ought Heaven&mdash;as if prepar'd to <HI>&s;wear</HI>.</L>
<L>The Tyrant &s;mil'd:&mdash;when &s;trait, the Prie&s;t look'd <HI>pale</HI>;</L>
<L>The Lights extingui&s;h'd&mdash;and the Temple's Roof,</L>
<L>Shook by de&s;cending Thunder, &s;eem'd to <HI>bow!</HI></L>
<L>The <HI>God!</HI> the <HI>God!</HI> the reverend Starter cry'd,</L>
<L><HI>Forbids the&s;e baneful Nuptials.</HI>&mdash;Yes: I HEAR him,</L>
<L>The dreadful <HI>Prince</HI> reply'd: and, at that Word,</L>
<L>Leapt, from the Altar, to the Tyrant's Brea&s;t&mdash;</L>
<L>And plung'd the &s;acred <HI>Axe</HI> of Sacrifice,</L>
<L>Snatch'd, like a Lightning's Fla&s;h! and reach'd his <HI>Life</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;He <HI>f$ll</HI>&mdash;and o'er him while with pendant Eye</L>
<L>Th' indignant Hero hung, with Arm new-rais'd,</L>
<L>Ba&s;e, from behind, pale <HI>Erox</HI> pierc'd his Side.</L>
<L>&mdash;Red, in his mingled Blood, and ri&s;ing Anger,</L>
<L>He heard the <HI>Crowd's protective Cry</HI>&mdash;turn'd &s;hort,</L>
<L>And buried in his Brow the rapid Steel.</L>
<L>Then, to the Altar's Height &s;ublimely &s;prung,</L>
<L>Stood, Monarch, all-confe&s;s'd; and <HI>wav'd</HI> the Throng.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Narb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>All, All, prodigious! and the Work of Heaven.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>I&s;m.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>How was the trembling Queen, mean while, employ'd?</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eur.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Silence, ye People, hear your King, &s;he cry'd,</L>
<L>Son of my Sorrows: hear <HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI>'s <HI>Gods</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;More, &s;he has &s;aid&mdash; but from the Temple's Porch,</L>
<L>The Tyrant's Guards ru&s;hed in, and All grew Tempe&s;t.</L>
<L>&mdash;Th' in&s;piring Prie&s;ts proclaim'd their Sovereign's Cau&s;e;</L>
<L>The People heard 'em: and a <HI>War</HI> of <HI>Wills</HI>,</L>
<L>And Swords cro&s;s-cla&s;hing, fill'd the <HI>Fane</HI> with Death.</L>
<L>Sudden, the Shrines, o'erthrown, were &s;tain'd with Blood;</L>
<L><PB N="79" REF="82">Cru&s;h'd Infants, in their &s;mother'd Mother's Arms,</L>
<L>Ga&s;p'd, and expir'd. Friends, Foes, Prie&s;t$, Strangers, All,</L>
<L>Heap'd on each other lay, one mingled Carnage!</L>
<L>Now flying, now returning, flows and ebbs,</L>
<L>From Side to Side, the pre&s;s'd and &s;houldring Stream.</L>
<L>&mdash;The Swell of Slaughter pu&s;h'd me thro' the Gate,</L>
<L>And veil'd the <HI>Queen</HI>, and her <HI>Eumenes</HI>, from me.</L>
<L>But to the la&s;t, long as my Sight cou'd hold her,</L>
<L>I &s;aw her, in the bloody Tide, oppo&s;ing,</L>
<L>Be&s;eeching, threat'ning; tiring every Limb,</L>
<L>And lo&s;ing every Prayer, to <HI>&s;ave Eumenes</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;But, &s;ee! Heaven's In&s;trument, the kind High Prie&s;t,</L>
<L>Is here &mdash; and calls for <HI>Narbas</HI>.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter High Prie&s;t.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>High Prie&s;t.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Good old Man!</L>
<L>To you, and to your Daughter's pitied Fears,</L>
<L>Our Queen, victorious, her doom'd Son, redeem'd</L>
<L>And Heaven, that loves the Ju&s;t, &s;end Peace and Joy.</L>
<L>&mdash;The People, by <HI>my</HI> timely Zeal appriz'd,</L>
<L>Won from the Tyrant's Cau&s;e, &s;u&s;tain the King.</L>
<L>The King, by more than mortal Force, in&s;pir'd,</L>
<L>Has, by one, great, determin'd, dreadful Blow,</L>
<L>To his high, injur'd, Race, his Country's Fame,</L>
<L>And murder'd Father's Gho&s;t, a bloody Victim,</L>
<L>Devoted! offer'd up the Tyrant's Soul.</L>
<L>&mdash;Death, and Revenge, and due Defence of Right.</L>
<L>Delug'd the Temple: and the Scene grew horrid.</L>
<L>When, to the Leaders of his furious Guards,</L>
<L>Who, through the direful Conflict, won their Way,</L>
<L>Pale <HI>Poliphontes</HI>, &s;truggling from his Pangs,</L>
<L><PB N="80" REF="83">And &s;tagg'ring painful, with expiring Eye,</L>
<L>Rais'd his now powerle&s;s Hand; bad Slaughter cea&s;e:</L>
<L>Call'd the Gods <HI>ju&s;t</HI> &mdash;and own'd th' inflicted <HI>Vengeance</HI>.</L>
<L>Then, at their Prince's Feet, th' a&s;toni&s;h'd Band</L>
<L>Fell pro&s;trate. Silence &s;trait took place of Up|roar:</L>
<L>Low knelt the Crowd, in Peace &mdash; Rebellion died&mdash;</L>
<L>And Awe, and Homage, felt th' in&s;piring <HI>God</HI>.</L>
<L>But, look, where Heaven's compleated Work appears.</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI> the La&s;t.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>To the Foregoing</HI> &mdash;Merop&eacute;, <HI>led by</HI> Eumenes, <HI>bloody. &mdash;Prie&s;ts. Guards. People. Shouts without: and Trumpets</HI>.</STAGE>
<STAGE>NARBAS, EURICLES, CHIEF PRIEST, <HI>and</HI> ISMEN&Eacute;, <HI>(All, &s;peak, kneeling,)</HI></STAGE>
<L>Hail! and be ever ble&s;s'd&mdash;O, King! Oh, Queen!</L>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mer.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>Ri&s;e&mdash;and lament no more, ye happy Friends</L>
<L>Of Virtue, and of Heaven!&mdash;See! what the Gods</L>
<L>Have done&mdash;to &s;hame Su&s;picion, into <HI>Faith!</HI></L>
<L>Oh! never let the Innocent <HI>de&s;pair:</HI></L>
<L>The Hand, that <HI>made</HI>, can <HI>&s;ave:</HI> and be&s;t knows <HI>when</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;But you, Heav'n's <HI>Herald!</HI> Envoy, of its Will!</L>
<L>And Image, of its Mercy! what, to <HI>you</HI>,</L>
<L>Shall my recov'ring Sen&s;e of Godhead &s;ay?</L>
<L>That dar'd, in Sorrow's Agony, <HI>forget</HI></L>
<L>The Di&s;tance, of High Heaven, from Human Weakne&s;s!</L>
<L><PB N="81" REF="84">Oh! call not Angui&s;h <HI>In&s;ult</HI>. Smile, on <HI>Wrongs:</HI></L>
<L>And ble&s;s the pitied Pang, amid&s;t its Ra&s;hne&s;s.</L>
<STAGE><HI>To</HI> Eumenes.</STAGE>
<L>&mdash;Son of <HI>Alcides:</HI>&mdash;for, what Heart, but <HI>His</HI>,</L>
<L>Nouri&s;h'd in Mi&s;ery! by Wants ob&s;tructed!</L>
<L>Ere &s;prung, like thine, at Youth's fir&s;t <HI>Shoot</HI>, to Glory?</L>
<L>Ere, for its fir&s;t E&s;&s;ay, o'erwhelm'd Oppre&s;&s;ion;</L>
<L>Trod on a Tyrant, and redeem'd a <HI>People?</HI></L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Eum.</HI></SPEAKER>
<L>'Tis but the low, the la&s;t, the lighte&s;t Duty</L>
<L>Of a <HI>King</HI>'s Hand, to <HI>dare</HI>. 'Tis His, to &s;ave;</L>
<L>To think, to hear, to labour, to di&s;cern,</L>
<L>To form, to remedy,&mdash;to <HI>be</HI>&mdash;but <HI>one:</HI></L>
<L>Yet, act, and love, and fear, and feel,&mdash;for <HI>A$l</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;Oh, Madam! I am yours, mid&s;t <HI>all</HI> the&s;e Claims.</L>
<L>Be Tho&s;e my Glory's, <HI>This</HI> my Duty's Care,</L>
<L>To add my Royal <HI>Father</HI>'s Love, to mine:</L>
<L>And, with a <HI>doubled</HI> Rev'rence, &s;eek your Comfort.</L>
<L>&mdash;Help me, good <HI>Euricles!</HI> in That &s;weet View:</L>
<L>Thou art no Stranger to its gen'rous Call &mdash;</L>
<L>And I will <HI>court</HI> Thy Coun&s;els &mdash; and <HI>reward</HI> 'em.</L>
<L>&mdash; <HI>Narbas!</HI> what Power can Language lend my Love,</L>
<L>To paint the Joy, <HI>Thy</HI> Sen&s;e of Plea&s;ure gives me?</L>
<L>Guide of my Infancy! my Life's long <HI>Saver!</HI></L>
<L>Light of my opening Mind! my Heart's fir&s;t <HI>Former!</HI></L>
<L>Thou Source, and Soul, and Author of my Vir|tues:</L>
<L>And every future Fame, the Gods may lend me!</L>
<L>&mdash;What can deficient Gratitude in&s;pire,</L>
<L>To &s;hew my <HI>Will to thank</HI> De&s;ert, like Thine?</L>
<STAGE><HI>Turns toward</HI> I&s;men&eacute;.</STAGE>
<L>Unle&s;s This &s;ofter Copy of thy Goodne&s;s,</L>
<L>Lovelie&s;t <HI>I&s;men&eacute;</HI>, &s;miles on my &s;weet Hope:</L>
<L><PB N="82" REF="85">And &s;toops to be a <HI>Queen</HI>&mdash;to ble&s;s her <HI>Father</HI>.</L>
<L>&mdash;I mark a meaning Blu&s;h, that looks Con&s;ent:</L>
<L>And <HI>hear</HI> thee, tho' thou &s;peak'&s;t not.&mdash;Till anon,</L>
<L>Su&s;pend we Thoughts, thus tender.&mdash;Let us, now,</L>
<L>Summon <HI>Mycen&eacute;</HI>'s <HI>Chiefs</HI>, and calm her People.</L>
<STAGE><HI>To</HI> Merop&eacute;.</STAGE>
<L>Come, Madam! He who <HI>reigns</HI>, but climbs to Care;</L>
<L><HI>Safe</HI>, th$' his Throne, he finds no <HI>Softne&s;s</HI>, there.</L>
<L>Danger and Doubts, and Toils, each Moment; &s;eize:</L>
<L>Hang on his Bu&s;ine&s;s &mdash; or perplex his Ea&s;e.</L>
<L>Bright, but by Pomp of <HI>Woe</HI>, Kings <HI>&s;hine</HI> in vain:</L>
<L>Envy'd, for <HI>Angui&s;h</HI>; and adorn'd, for Pain!</L>
</SP>
</DIV3>
